lign: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10. Why or how will treatment care or support be likely to reduce harm, or deterioration, or<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>result</p><p style="text-align: center;">in an improvement to the person's condition?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Â  Â  Â  Â Wendell had untreated mental illness for many years. He remains ambivalent<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>regarding the need for help and support going forward and is vulnerable to the idea<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>that he can do it alone He has numerous goals that he can achieve with appropriate<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>help but he is at risk of further relapse without support and he is not yet able or<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>appreciate the demands of his illness and the need he has to moderate arid modify<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>his life style and some of his choices.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">11<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>.Why can't the treatment care or support be adequately provided with less restriction of the freedom of choice and movement of the person?</p><p style="text-align: center;">Attempt has been made to manage Wendell in a less restricted way however th 1"e).iide11c1f/Â  of'full f</p><p style="text-align: center;">insight is notyet<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>preasent and tne risks rem irr.high.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell re.acts adversely when the reasons of why the treatment order is in place are raised as discussion points as Wendell firmly believes he shouldn't be subjected to the treatment order</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p