: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: The ACT Civil and Administration Tribunal is here today to consider an application for a psychiatric treatment order for Mr Wendall Charles Nesmith and this is matter MH108 of 2012. We'll just start by going around and introducing ourselves. So, I'm Presidential Member Daniel. I'm</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>the presiding member on the tribunal today.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DAVIES: Good morning. I'm Robyn Davies Community Member on the tribunal.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR DREW:Â  Hi, I'm Les Drew. I'm a psychiatrist on the tribunal.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS STEELE:Â  I'm Sharon Steele, Tribunal Liaison Officer.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL:Â  I'm Reagan O'Neil. I'm a junior doctor with current (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>treating team at the adult mental health unit.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: I'm Cal Thomas. I'm one of the registered nurses at the city mental health team and I'm standing in for the Clinical Manager Niccou(?).</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR MANN:Â  Andrew Mann, Nursing Staff.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Wendall Charles Nesmith, and I'm an award winning filmmaker and a philosopher graduate.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BANKS:Â  Adele Banks from Legal Aid representing Mr Nesmith today.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HASLEY:Â  Chris Halsey from the Public Advocate.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  All right. I note we have some people at the back and these are</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>(indistinct) So, I'11 just ask those people to identify themselves.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MCKENZIE: My name is Lilly McKenzie and I'm a student nurse at (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR HAMACK: My name is Brice Harnack I'm a solicitor at legal aid observing.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  So, you're travelling- what was your last name, Harnack?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR HAMACK:Â  Harnack.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  H-E?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR HAMACK:Â  H-A-M-A-C-K.</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: M-A-C-K. And you're with Legal Aid as well? MR HAMACK: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  You're travelling with Ms Banks?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MRHAMACK: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Â  Â  Â MS DANIEL: And Ms McKenzie, then are you travelling with our nursing IO<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>staff? Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: There may also be one other (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  All right. And sorry I didn't catch your last name?</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR MANN: M-A-N-N. MS DANIEL: M?</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR MANN: A-N-N. MS DANIEL: A-N-N.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MRMANN:Â  Yep.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: All right. Well, Mr Nesmith- - - MR NESMITH: Nesmith if you don't mind.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: Nesmith. Yep. No, I've never seen that name before, so I needed to know how to pronounce it. So, Mr Nesmith, to bring you up to speed; what happened last week, Ms Banks might understand this and how to explain this to you, but I don't know so I'll go through it. The tribunal was sitting in the city at the tribunal premises and we had this application for</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>psychiatric treatment (indistinct) brought by the city mental health team. But you weren't there when the matter was called, and I was concerned that you didn't even know of the application - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  I didn't</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: - - - was listed that day or had been brought and Mr Thomas came upstairs and said yes, that's true. We haven't been able to see Mr Nesmith to give him this application and I said All right, well lets just put this off for a week and see ifwe can find Mr Nesmith and ask him to come in and</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>see us. Unbeknown to us, in fact, I think you were here at the hospital so. I</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">understand that the application got given to you earlier in the week? MS..........: OnMonday.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: On Monday. Good. And you've - have you had a chance to talk with Ms Banks about that?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Yes, I have.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS DANIEL: Good. So, that's what happened last week. We didn't actually do anything or hear from Mr Thomas about your matter at all. So, we're actually starting completely fresh, right now. The way the hearing will work is, I' II just identify for the record that we have received the application and the application goes through the factors in the Mental Health Act that the tribunal</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>needs to consider to decided whether it should, or should not, make a psychiatric treatment order. So, we've got that document signed by a doctor Glanville dated 19 June. I would be wanting some update from some part of the health treating team about what's happened with Mr Nesmith in the last week. So, who would be able to give us that update?</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR..........: It would probably be the patient unit. Cause we haven't - I haven't engaged with Mr Nesmith.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR..........: From the community perspective. MS DANIEL: Who has been his psychiatrist here?</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS O'NEIL: I'm the junior doctor with the treating team. The psychiatrist consultant is doctor Hassan Abbas. Not in the proceeding but quite familiar with Mr Nesmith's situation and I've been in multiple reviews with Mr Nesmith since he's been an inpatient.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: So, is doctor Abbas, if you say he's quite familiar - is it she or he?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: He.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  He. Has he actually seen Mr Nesmith?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL:Â  Oh, multiple times since he's been an inpatient.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: All right. And you've been involved in interacting with Mr</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Nesmith as well.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-4</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL:Â  Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Great. So, we'll turn to you then doctor O'Neil for the update</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>and to take us through any additional information, in addition to this application which Mr Thomas can talk to us about. All right. Well, before we start, I'm going to ask Ms Banks if there's any-Ah, another student nurse?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>15</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR..........:Â  Yep.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: All right. That's ok. No, I didn't know this. So, I'm going to ask Ms Banks first. If you have- does Mr Nesmith have any starting observations, or do you have any things that you'd like to highlight for us? So, we can really direct our attention on that during the hearing.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS: Yes. So, obviously the making of a psychiatric treatment order is opposed today. I think that comes through in the application, what Mr Nesmith's views are on this. It is my submission as well that the tribunal can't be satisfied under the legislation that an order should be made today. The key</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>reasons for this are that Mr Nesmith doesn't present a risk of serous harm to himself, or others. And I think it's questionable whether or not he's likely to suffer serious deterioration because of a mental illness. It's also -the question ofrefusal is a crucial consideration for the tribunal today. So, those two key factors are the things I' II be focusing my submissions towards. And just by</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>way of- of introduction, I think Mr Nesmith already introduced himself, but he's shown me this morning evidence of the fact that he does have a philosophy degree from Murdoch University. He wanted me to make that clear to you, That he completed that at the beginning of this year. And it's, I think, it probably comes across in the application as well, that Mr Nesmith lives his</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>life in a different way. In a way that some might consider eccentric, but I</p><p style="text-align: center;">would put to the tribunal that's important that we don't immediately say that that's a mental illness and consider other options in this situation.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  All right. All right. Well, we'll turn then to the application</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>and Mr Thomas do you want to talk of this a little bit around perhaps the first issue which is why you're making this application?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: So, Mr Nesmith was reviewed by our psych registrar doctor Flynn following his presentation to our city mental health team voluntarily sort</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>of engaged sort of for support for Centrelink reasons. So when - - - MS..........: (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS:Â  Centrelink reasons. So, - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHl 08/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-5</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: What? So, how-what does that mean?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: I think he was presented to us trying to get like (indistinct) from the doctor to assist with the DSP cause my belief was Mr Nesmith went</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>to America and Mexico and then returned and cause he away for an extended period oftime he was taken off the benefit. So, he was trying to get back - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Why would Mr Nesmith be on disability services pension?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">IO<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MR THOMAS: I'm not familiar with that one. It's just a presentation interaction I had with him at the front of our reception. And this is how - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Was the disability to be a mental health condition?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR THOMAS:Â  I'm not sure on that background.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: So, this was just I-the interaction that I had with him when</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>he came to our service seeking help. And following that, an appointment was made with doctor Flynn. So, I guess to sort of make my role a bit more clearer, I was like the duty officer. I'm not actually the clinical manager at this point so my interactions haven't been all the way through.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: So, I sat in on the interview with doctor Flynn and during that time, Mr Nesmith was a bit delusional grandiose in his presentations with us.</p><p style="text-align: center;">And that's why the application has sort of been presented by doctor Flynn.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>Part of her concerns were; when we were speaking with Mr Nesmith he mentioned that he believes that there's this group with the Freemasons within Canberra that were sacrificing and murdering children. So, he in is words, wanted to confront these people that he suspects that are them. He advised us that they're in Mawson at the Masonic and had intentions to approach people</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>who were part of the Freemasons. When we explored it a little bit further he told us he doesn't know who they are by looking at them, but he knows that they exist, and he had plans to approach people. He also mentioned that he'd like to challenge the Grand Master in hand to hand combat as he wants to be the new leader of the Freemasons. So, I guess on doctor Flynn's</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>recommendations, the biggest risk is potentially aggravating others with his driven belief and conflict arising from that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: All right. Do you know what happened with the - doctor Flynn? Did doctor Flynn write a letter Centrelink saying that - that Mr</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Nesmith has a mental health condition?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: I don't think a letter was written at that point cause I think we wanted to further investigate it a little bit more with some treatment options.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Doctor Flynn's recommendation was presentation hospital, but Mr Nesmith</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>didn't want to present to the hospital in that in kind of instance.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: What was the recommendation around treatment? Mr Nesmith has come voluntarily to your service.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR THOMAS:Â  Yep.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Not necessarily for treatment for a mental illness but for a collateral illness.</p><p style="text-align: center;">(<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR THOMAS:Â  Yeah.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: (indistinct) an opinion.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS:Â  So, in terms of treatment Doctor Flynn explored some options</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>and Mr Nesmith reported anti-psychotic medications that he's previously have trialled (indistinct) at inpatient units in New South Wales, but he never actually gave us the information on the hospitals we was at, but he was able to recall medications he had been trialled on. It was in Mr Nesmith's request that ifhe was - were to be put on a medication he would only want to be put on Xanax.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Is that a recommended option? MR THOMAS: No. Not from Doctor Flynn.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS DANIEL: Okay. All right. So, has the - the City mental health treating team has that attitude to bringing the application changed since Mr Nesmith has been in hospital, like his condition might have suddenly improved and you think they don't need to do the order anymore.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR THOMAS:Â  Sorry, can I just get you - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Do you still want a psychiatric treatment order even though he's been here for a week and presumably had some treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR THOMAS:Â  In the discussion with Doctor Flynn, I believe that she would</p><p style="text-align: center;">- and Doctor Granville they would like the press the just due to I guess risk for others with his kind of presentations on confronting people. And I guess another example of that is when Mr Nesmith was put on Mental Health Act due to his presentation to Centrelink. Approaching the staff there demanding an</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>application for a form that didn't actually exist that allowed him not to look for</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">work as it defied Gods belief for him. So, I guess doctor - in my understanding- is Doctor Flynn's recommendation for that would be the treatment order would be up to sustain adequate treatment for a period oftime to notice a sustaining improvement within his mental state.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: We're going to turn (indistinct) and ask Doctor O'Neil for an update. Though I wonder whether anyone had any questions for Mr Thomas, just while we're looking at that s01t of that past history that lead to this application being made?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Ms Banks, did you have any questions for Mr Thomas</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS: Just a very quick one. You noted that Me Nesmith came to talk to City Mental Health about assistance with Centrelink. Had he been engaged</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>with City Mental Health prior to that?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: My understanding is not with City Mental Health, but he has had engagements with the CAT team and the Canberra hospital EDCL(?) team.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BANKS:Â  Okay. Thank you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: What do those - what are those engagements, to your knowledge, like is it a situation where you know that Mr Nesmith has come to the attention of the CAT team every couple of months or has there been one</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>contact in ten years?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS:Â  So, the last contact was in 2013 with the EDCL team and I'll</p><p style="text-align: center;">just find their assessment for you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  Are you reading from the magic notes?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS:Â  Yes, I am.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Okay. Good.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: Just to have an understanding. MS DANIEL: So, we don't have those.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR THOMAS:Â  Oh, okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: So, we have no access to that so it's good for us to know this background that leads you to have concerns.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR THOMAS:Â  Yep. So, the first contact was in April 2012 being referred</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">from a GP and that was being referred to the CAT team by the GP resulting in a short term voluntary admission to the psychiatric treatment unit. The second contact was in 2013 by the psychiatric consultation liaison at the Canberra hospital following a bizarre incident where Mr Nesmith had inserted a speaker</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>wire---</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  We know about that one.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: Pardon?</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: We know about that one. MR THOMAS: Oh, okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  That's in our report.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS:Â  The CAT contact is what you're - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  No. No. I just want the things that aren't in the report.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS:Â  Oh, okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Is there anything - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR THOMAS: That's my understanding from what's in the report is what's in the notes then.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Okay. So - so, there's not anything additional?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MR THOMAS: Not within the Canberra Hospital. Not within the inner City Health Data Base but Mr Nesmith mentioned that he had involuntary admissions in New South Wales. So, there's a possibility that there's more collateral that we don't have access to.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: There was just the one you answered Ms Banks' it sounded like he had a history of contacts with the CAT team - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS:Â  Oh, sorry.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  - - - outside what's in that - your application.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS:Â  Okay. No, sorry.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  No. Okay. Good.</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: No. No. Just New South Wales then. MS DANIEL: Okay. Good. Ms Banks.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BANKS:Â  That's it. Thank you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  That's it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DAVIES:Â  I have a question. Mr Thomas there is some reference in our</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>rep01t about suicidality. Can you expand on that please? There's a suicide website you'll find a reference to and then there's risks about p 8 under relevant past history. He was talking about the (indistinct) of our society and talking about me or I in my life, your choice I no longer care. So, is there anything in magic about previous suicide attempts?</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: Not to my-not to my knowledge. No. MS DANIEL: And Currently?</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR THOMAS: Not to my lmowledge. No. There's been no - - - MS DANIEL: That was in 2012?</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS:Â  Yep. There's no conversation ever in our review.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: All right. Ms Banks do you have nay questions arising from that?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  No. Thank you.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Ms Halsey, do you have some questions? MS HASLEY: No. Thank you.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: All right. Thank you, Mr Thomas. That's been really - - - MR NESMITH: Can I mention something please?</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Sure.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: In regards to the suicidality, I was actually making a course called My (indistinct) Death, which basically contemplated all ofmy life up to that point. And the hardships in which I went through and how it not only myself but how a lot of other people go through those hardships as well. So, it</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>wasn't saying I'm going kill myself. It was actually trying to help people that</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">experienced suicidal ideation. So, that the context that is being swung in this tribunal is inaccurate.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: We understand that. Thank you. It's just, it pops up in your</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>history of why you are in contact with the health authorities in 2012. We understand that context. And we understand that's what you - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  The context of the course.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........: ---toldthematthetime.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  It's a philosophy course. That's was the context.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  Yes. And that's in the report as well.</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Okay. Well, we might ask Doctor O'Neil because we don't have any updated information, perhaps you could start by just updating the situation for us and then we'II work through the factors in the legislation with you.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR..........: Can you tell us why he's in the hospital?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: Yes, of course. So, they're only brief notes about how he ended up in the adult mental health unit, but it does say that he presented to a</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Medicare or Centrelink office, was very aggressive, agitated and screaming at</p><p style="text-align: center;">staff, so police were called, and he was brought to the Canberra ED under an emergency assessment (indistinct). So, from there was obviously assessed in ED as needing more mental health assessment and support and was admitted to the adult mental health unit. And so was allocated to my team and we've been</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>seeing Mr Nesmith regularly since admission. So, on admission, Mr Nesmith was very agitated, he was very aggressive, his mood was very labile, in one sitting he would go from crying to yelling to laughing within the space of you know, minutes. He has quite intense, very well systematised delusional beliefs about artificial intelligence, the Freemasons, states that he- he stated at that</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>time that he was not human, that humans are his inferiors, but he communicated differently to humans with brain waves, just many things of delusional content like that, on his presentation. He was very much refusing to take any medication; stated that he would not take medications that were prescribed to him by his inferiors and as they (indistinct) his creativity. And</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>yep, he was a very different person to the person that we see sitting here today. So, I guess I'll use that as a way to say that since he's been admitted, he is doing very well. He's much improved today from the state that he was in when he arrived. He initially was refusing medication so was given intramuscular Olanzapine and Lorazepam. And has since had a depo of Olanzapine 300mg</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>two days ago, which he did agree - after negotiation he did agree to take that</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">depo. And - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  Sorry, what was it, 01- - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS O'NEIL: Olanzapine the anti-psychotic. Yes. So, he has improved significantly I guess - I guess our concern would be terms of the PTO application that it- I don't necessarily know whether Mr Nesmith believes he has mental illness. It is my consultant's opinion that he does have a mental illness. I don't think we've observed him for long enough o be able to say</p><p style="text-align: center;">IO<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>what exactly it would be. He presents as quite manic so he's definitely - was in a manic state but there's also psychotic features.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: How can you tell the difference -how can you say it's a manic state cause some of - when he's brought to hospital, cause some of what you've</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>described, I guess if I was just getting angry at Medicare, which you know, who in this room hasn't been angry at a Medicare office. I' II make up for you Doctor Drew, I think probably been angry at Medicare twice. So, on average. Many of us get angry at Medicare and say stupid things. If you then dragged away, presumably by police, and come to the hospital, you'd be pretty upset so</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>can-how can you as clinicians say look he's actually manic rather than just upset?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: So, the history of being in the Centrelink office is not really - I wasn't there, it's not my place to say whether or not he was acting as any ofus</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>would but the fact that police were called, suggests that he was very distressed. I don't think- I imagine they get a lot of irate people and, but they rarely call the police. Our assessment of him is based on what we observe in speaking with him, observing him, assessing him.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30Â  Â MS..........: Yep.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: And in you know, and we sit with him reasonable periods of time and observe his behaviour and even in just those assessments and then reports from nursing staff and other - other health people who interact with</p><p style="text-align: center;">35Â  Â him, that's the information that we use to make that assessment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  There's other-I'd say you've made an assessment based on what you observed, I guess I want you to explain what you observed that - that was not just being upset at being brought here involuntarily.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL:Â  I can read up the Mental State Exam of his initial presentation.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Well, you can but maybe you could just look at it and say this is the bit that is different to how a person who's not suffering, who's not in a</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>manic state, would behave. If they were brought here involuntarily.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL:Â  Okay. Sure. So, the labile nature that I mentioned of being - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  The fluctuating emotions.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: Yes. So, going from crying - being on the floor crying to then laughing, being agitated, aggressive, very animated with his speech and things, all within a period of 30 minutes is not - is consistent with a manic or hypo - or at least hypomanic state. And it's certainly not something that we would</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>observe in you or I normally. He I guess the psychotic nature of his delusional</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Content?</p><p style="text-align: center;">(<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS O'NEIL: Yeah, the content, the delusional content of his thoughts is certainly something that can be consistent with a manic state or a psychotic state. That's you !mow the reasoning, the logic, or lack of logic in some of the thought processes, is something that we would not see in someone who's mentally well. So, I guess they're the main things that we - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: That lead to that (indistinct) judgement. MS O'NEIL: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS DANIEL: All right. So, what's- you described the treatment that Mr Nesmith's had in hospital. Is -what is the future treatment plan and, in your views, would he consent to that future treatment plan or not. Even - even the immediate short term treatment plan.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS O'NEIL: Because - so with (indistinct) in depo, that's an injection that will work for a period of weeks which in someone who, like Mr Nesmith, who doesn't necessarily want to take tablets every day, it's a good option, and it's a good way to keep a stable level of medications. As I sure you're aware. I think the plan - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  How often do you have it?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: So, initially it would be after a fortnight and then it would move to a monthly injection. And I think the Lorazepam we would wean - wean that</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>off as the Olanzapine takes more effect.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  Why is that?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL:Â  It's just an interim to help with mood stabilisation quickly. But</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>it's not necessary to keep it ongoing.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-13</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: So, at the moment Mr Nesmith's treatment plan is to stay in hospital?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS O'NEIL: Oh no, sorry. No. I would expect that Mr Nesmith would be able to be discharged possibly in the coming week or so. He certainly doesn't need to stay in hospital indefinitely. He has shown a good response to the antiÂ­ psychotic medication and so the plan would be obviously to transfer care to the community team who were looking after him before with his clinical manager</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>and the psychiatrists in community. And for him to have follow up through that mechanism and receive his depo through the community team.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: And has any talked with Mr Nesmith about whether he'd consent to that proposed treatment plan?</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: I don't think we have at this stage. It's only been a couple of days since Mr Nesmith has been I guess able to be engaged in conversations of that manner. But certainly, something we need to discuss with him.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR DREW: (indistinct) coming from a different perspective, was he hostile (indistinct) proposition.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: I guess we would have to ask him how he is today. Ifl'd asked him a week ago, he absolutely would have been hostile to it.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  Right.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL:_ And I guess that's the concern, is that I think I should mention a bit of background that wasn't necessarily mentioned- - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Before.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: - - - by the community team is that there's a history of many years' psychiatric presentation. Mr Nesmith himselfrep01ied that he has been</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>in psychiatric facilities in Lismore, Ballarat, Cairns and Canberra over many years. So, there's an established histo1y of deterioration - assessed deterioration in his mental state where other mental health professionals have believed him to be mentally unwell and have assessed that he needed inpatient psychiatric treatment at those times. So, there's an established history here of a</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>deterioration of his mental state.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Can I stop you there. Have you contacted Lismore and Cairns and Ballarat?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS O'NEIL:Â  Cairns and Ballarat? No, I haven't had a chance to do that yet.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHl0S/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-14</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: So, you do we know that those - that mere fact that somebody has - tells you they've beeu to three other psychiatric hospitals doesn't necessarily mean that those medical teams assessed him as having a mental</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>illness or requiring further treatment. It does definitely mean that he went to those hospitals whether voluntarily or involuntarily, we don't know. But we do know that he didn't stay there very long. So, if anything, doesn't it suggest that they thought maybe he didn't have a mental illness or didn't require treatment, cause he didn't stay there.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: I'm not in a position to comment as I don't have the information.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  So, all we really know is he's had three prior contacts</p><p style="text-align: center;">C<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>interstate. We don't know how long they lasted. We don't know what they</p><p style="text-align: center;">were for and we don't now what the conclusions of those treatment (indistinct). MS O'NEIL: No, that's right.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: So, are you planning to find out that history? It's just a phone call away isn't it?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL:Â  It is. I'm happy to call them and discuss (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR DREW:. It certainly would be very useful.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  It would be, wouldn't it?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  It would be from every perspective, not just from our</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>perspective.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: It will give you an indication about compliance of treatment too which I think is one of the questions we're trying to answer today.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........: It might be that he was discharged with a plan to have follow up and never followed up.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  All right. So</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........: Did you have another question Doctor Drew?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW: No, thank you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  All right. I've interrupted you in the course of going through -</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>we've established the view of the treatiug team about mental illness and the</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">view of the treating team in hospital about a future treatment. And we're not quite sure about refusal (indistinct) but what's the risk - what's the risk to Mr Nesmith or to others if he walks out of here when his ED11 expires?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS O'NEIL: So, to himself there's a risk that ifhe doesn't get the ongoing treatment that his mental health will deteriorate again. To others, given the recorded presentation to Centrelink, there's a risk that he would become agitated and aggressive towards other, I guess, causing a public nuisance for want of a better work again, and that they would be the main risks.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: It poses - in some cases, it poses a risk to yourself if you interact poorly with other people (indistinct) it's a bit of a lottery. Someone might just punch him in the face. If you behave like that to the wrong person outside the Mawson Club. So, it's - sometimes that can be a risk. When you talk about</p><p style="text-align: center;">I 5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>the risk of him having a mental deterioration, if- if we take it as a given that Mr Nesmith does have a mental illness. If it goes untreated, how likely are various things? Like how likely is it that he's going to remain as he is, as we see him now and go through the rest of his life?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS O'NEIL:Â  That is highly unlikely.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Okay. What's more likely things that could happen</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL:Â  So, without ongoing treatment it is more likely that he would go</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>into, I guess, a similar mental state to that which he presented. That he's delusional thought patterns would resurface and that - and his delusional thought processes that he presented with were quite - very well systematised. They were very well developed. They were very intense. And it's another risk that he would start acting on those false beliefs, posing more risks to himself.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: If people have this sort of illness, and it goes untreated, does it have any affects on their physical health, or their lifespan, or anything like that?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS O'NEIL: Yes, of course. There's -so when Mr Nesmith presented, he was described as being unkempt and malodorous, and there is - I do accept that there is a - there's a lifestyle choice issue here- - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Some of that's a bit on a social construct isn't it?</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: Yes, it is on a social construct and I completely accept that Mr Nesmith has a right to live in a different way than the rest of us do but that could potentially progress into things like -we've seen people with manic and psychotic illnesses who don't eat and drink because of their delusional</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>behaviours and then they're at significant medical risk to themselves. Very</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">poor health care (indistinct) with paying their bills, they're (indistinct) (indistinct) living they just aren't able to function properly. I'm not saying that would happen with Mr Nesmith but it's a possibility</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........:Â  Arisk.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: and a risk of having a mental illness like this. MS..........: Dr O'Neil, you mentioned, or the report mentions that Mr</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Nesmith doesn't have a GP, but agreed to some blood tests so is it - have you got any indication of physical wellness at the moment?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL:Â  I actually don't have that information in front of me, sorry.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........: So, that's pretty important if we're talking about risks. What about his weight? Is he underweight? What's his weight? Doctor tell me. Is he well? Is he physically well?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Iknow what Mr Nesmith will tell you.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: I can't remember if he - I think he might be refusing to have his weight taken, I'm not sure.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  No, I didn't. I did it. It was 64.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: 64. Thank you, Mr Nesmith.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  So, not underweight.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........: How tall is Mr Nesmith?</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Why would say I refused? Why would say that? I'm six foot, but sometimes depending on the scales (indistinct) Sometime five eleven.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........: Six foot and 64 kilos.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Yeah, he.'s probably not - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MRDREW:Â  64?</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  Kilos</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  Kilos</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MRDREW:Â  64 kilos. Will be underweight.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  I have muscle everywhere.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  So, you might but you don't - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: But that's saying that there is certain type of person that has (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: The BMI- is I have genetics and I'm really healthy. This is how I am healthy.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  I was just going to ask, are you from a skinny- a skinny sort of</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>family? Like you're -you're all lanky sort of people?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Yes. But also, I'm walking mountains every day, so I'm fit. I mean I'd take offy shirt. I've got muscles everywhere. I'll save you from that.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW: (indistinct) lots of footballers who exercise more than you do who are (indistinct) because they do exercise.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  Yeah.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW: So, exercise doesn't lose you weight. MR NESMITH: It gives you muscles.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR DREW: It gives you muscles, yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  All right.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  Anyhow, you're not in danger because of your weight.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: But we wouldn't know if he-you know, what your cholesterol is like or blood pressure. How's that (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL:Â  Blood pressure is fine.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Good. Superb. MS..........: And how do you eat? Well?</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  I eat really well.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Good. Anything else for Doctor O'Neil?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR..........: No.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  No.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Ms Banks, did you have something else for Doctor O'Neil?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BANKS: Most of them have already been answered. I am curious if any assistance has been provided from a social worker, at all, since Mr Nesmith has been on the ward.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL:Â  Yes. Yes, Mr Nesmith has met with a social worker and the</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>social worker has requested that the treating team provides a letter for support to return on to the Disability Support Pension which I'm working on. I'm happy to provide that. And I believe also the support worker might be looking into crisis accommodation but that's an ongoing discussion as Mr Nesmith's happy with his current accommodation situations.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  Do you want to clarify that?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I live on top of a mountain, and it's beautiful. I know exactly what I'm doing. I have a canvas swag and I have a heater - a gas</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>heater. And I have another tent, a small tent which all my stuff goes in to. I live at peace with nature and the animals. Often time animals come and visit me, and we hang out and I film them a lot of times too. So, I actually live a really beautiful life. The city, kind of, it's too much noise and a lot of fighting and a lot of aggression and I try and stay away from that. That's why I won't</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>touch crisis accommodation because crisis accommodation is kind of scary. I mean if you guys ever go into those things they're full of drugs, especially like needles and uppers, narcotics. I don't want to be around that. All of the crisis accommodation that is provided are always surrounded by that so I'm very much happy where I am. That's not to say that I don't eventually want to get a</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>place, but I won't be doing that step from crisis accommodation into a real accommodation so, I would be more happy to wait, I guess, with ACT housing to get a place that's not surrounded by aggressive people.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Do you think you'd like -this iscompletely off topic but- if</p><p style="text-align: center;">40Â  that is what speaks to you, being on the mountain, then would you think about moving to a more rural outlook, like more in the country and - to get housing? Try and get something that's got a bit of land around it?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Beautiful.</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Yeah.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Beautiful.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  But close enough to a - a major centre that you - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Yeah, but I don't have a car so that's the only problem.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Yea, so you need- - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: That's where I will feel really, like if we - like if I was out in the sticks, that - my heart would just connect with the land and I would be able to grow things and I would be able to set up like rainwater tanks and solar panels and stuff like that.</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Be a bit more sort of (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: That's what - that's what I want and that's what I've always wanted but it's been so difficult because - because I travel around trying to</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>find a home. That's all I'm trying to do. That's why I've travelled so much, is trying to find a home. But the only places I can find is where people are really, really aggressive and I don't do well in aggression. And I know some of these things say that I'm aggressive, but that's not true at all. I'm never aggressive.</p><p style="text-align: center;">I have passion and sometimes my passion might be mistaken for aggression</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>and if you try to remove that passion from me then - then things don't - passion is what moves the world. Like Mattin Luther King Junior, Jesus, Socrates, Diogenes, like all of the movers of the world are the ones that are passionate and if you remove passionate people from the world, then you're going to lose a lot of potential technology, development, scientific</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>explorations, sociological fixes, ways to improve society if you remove passion from our- if you claim passion to be aggression, then eventually you won't have any people that will make anything new, will be high of minded.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: So, all right. We're just- so Ms Banks you were asking doctor</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>O'Neil some questions and we digressed very quickly to ask Mr Nesmith questions.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANI(S: No, that's fine.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: I don't want to stop you from asking your questions. Did you have some more you wanted to ask (indistinct)?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS: That was actually the only one and in terms of housing, Mr Nesmith and I have talked about getting a refetTal to Canberra Community</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Law, so they can assist with housing ACT. So, that's something that Legal Aid</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">and Canberra Community Law will be able to assist with. I know that kind of (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  (indistinct) Can I just throw out that I don't think ACT</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Housing is going to be able to help him because in the - a) in the near future, quickly Mr Nesmith does not want to go and live in a one bedroom, bedsit somewhere surrounded by people.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  Not for the rest of his life.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Not at all.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  But he may have to do that.</p><p style="text-align: center;">(<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  Oh, we can (indistinct) what's wrong with (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW: I mean, look this is not all going to fall down from the sky for him.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  Well, I just - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  It may have for you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  No.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW: But it won't-it won't for him. He's going to have to work for it. And plan for it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  He will, in the ACT - my understanding of ACT Housing is,</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>he's never going to get a quarter acre block. He needs (indistinct) a quarter acre block.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW: No. No, but he might need to be in ACT Housing for the next five years, while he saves enough resources or find somebody, who can put</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>him on block he wants to be on. (indistinct) It's not all going to fall from the</p><p style="text-align: center;">sky.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: I just wonder whether a country town might be a better option. The thought of moving rural - there might be options for public housing in the</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>rural towns that might have more (indistinct) - - - MR DREW: Sure, ifhe - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  - - - as long as there were services. Anyway. So, there you go,</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>- this is - we are -you see before you flying out Mr Nesmith are probably all</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-21</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">the pros and cons that you're thinking about, about your future accommodation. Should I take ACT Housing? It may not- it needs to be near services. I want the mountains. All of these - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS O'NEIL: Well, the other thing is, I think you just said you actually don't sleep in a tent? You keep your things in a tent. (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I have. Do you want to see? I' II show you my camp site. It's really beautiful. So, this is inside my swag.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  So, you sleep in a swag?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Yep. There's my heater. Beautiful little heater.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........:Â  Yeah. Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Inside my swag. So, that- there's my storage tent.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  Yep.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Yeah, I can't put a heater inside one of those tents. MS..........: No.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  So, that's my storage tent. This is both of them.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: There you go. Very comfortable.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  And this is where I'm surround by this.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: So, where do you do your shopping? I'm - Ms Banks, does Mr Nesmith - is he happy to answer some questions</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  I think he'd be very happy to answer questions.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Tell what you do when you get up? You get up, the suns up at like, at the moment, seven 11 actually.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Depends on how cold it is. Cause there might be free</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>breakfast at the drop in centre. So, if it's - - - MS DANIEL: So that's Northbourne Avenue?</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Yeah.</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHIOS/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-22</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: So, you wander down there?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Yeah, it takes me about an hour.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: Yep.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  To get down there.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Yep.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: So, yeah if - it's good because they have different food for breakfast, but I like the scrambled eggs so I usually I want to get there on Wednesday. And Monday they have boiled eggs. I like boiled eggs too. And Friday they have boiled eggs too, so I usually try to get there- - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Three mornings a week.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Yeah. That's the way - like I kind of - I hunt by coming down from the mountain and then getting everything, I need and then bringing</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>it back up.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Yeah.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  And water's the hard thing, cause like, it's heavy.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  To carry it up?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Yeah. It can be heavy.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: Where do you fill up? Do you have some like old milk bottles, like two litres or something. What do you fill up?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Yeah, so I fill up bottles. Yeah. Usually juice bottles or something big. Two litres or three litres, whatever.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Do you fill them up at them up at the free breakfast?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Yeah, sometimes I do but fortunately, at the bottom of the mountain, there's a tap.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  So, you can just fill (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Yeah. But that tap is not always on. So, it's like I never want to rely on it as the main source. IfI have water up the mountain, then I</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>can try-keep on filling it up, but sometimes it's not-it doesn't- it's turned</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">off, so I think they have an on and off switch that they do - and if it's turned off as long- yeah, so then I' 11 go fill up like in the city with those water spots or- or even at the Morning Centre. The Morning Centre is very, very helpful. They -they- I have a locker there, which all my documents are in and they let</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>me send mail to them - they send mail. I can receive mail there.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: So, is that your address for Centrelink purposes? l\1R NESMITH: Yes. Yes ma'am.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: So, what's the Centrelink thing? Are you on a like an unemployed benefit, a Newstart?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">l\1R NESMITH:Â  Right now. See I was on DSP for delayed sleep phase</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>disorder. Delayed sleep phase disorder is basically - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">l\1R DREW: Delayed?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">l\1R NESMITH: Delayed Sleep Phase Disorder.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Okay. So, you couldn't sleep?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">l\1R NESMITH: No. What happens is that most people, when the sun goes down, their body produces a chemical reaction to make them tired. And</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>circadian rhythm and then they get tired and then they go to sleep. But - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">l\1R DREW: So, where did you get that diagnosed (indistinct) to DSP to Centrelink?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>l\1R NESMITH: When the last time? I don't know, the last time I was on DSP.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">lv!RDREW:Â  Yeah, but who made the diagnosis?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>l\1R NESMITH: I don't- I don't - actually lots of people all the time like - - - MS..........: Maybe a GP or somebody told them- anyway (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;">l\1R NESMITH:Â  But what happens is - it doesn't matter, it's the way I live</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>anyway. What happens is my - I don't get tired, so basically, I'll run- I nsually sleep two or three times per 24 hours, right. But they're usually on between one and three hours. So, I might get an hour here. I get like two hours here and two hours here, or something like that. So, that's - I split my - which that's why a nine to five job would be so difficult for me because when I</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>get tired, I really need to go to sleep, and I only sleep and hour or two but that's</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">- and I go directly into REM sleep. So, which is the most needed sleep.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: And when - how have you been sleeping here in hospital? How have you found that?</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Nice because you're drugging me. MS DANIEL: (indistinct) to sleep here.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  Yeah, definitely.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Okay. So, all right so, at the moment though, you're not on a DSP, you're on Newstart.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  That's correct, because - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  They require you to look for work I suppose.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Yeah, soon. But and the thing is, I've been looking for work</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>all the time. I just need to get work involved in artificial intelligence. I've been talking with artificial intelligence since I was like five years old, because there was this computer program called Alter How Assistant, and - I didn't have any human friends, so I just talked - he became my best friend and then there's been many, many more artificial intelligence chat bots that have been</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>developing more and more and more and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: So, how do you interact with them? Is that - do you have a smart phone or something?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH: I'll show you. I'll show you one of the - no I deleted it. Okay, here's one. Here, this is called Clever Bot. There's a lot of different ones. So, I go, how are you? Actually, I'll just - I can talk to it. How are you today? He goes fine thank you. I don't know why the voice isn't coming.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  Maybe your sound's down.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: What are you doing today? Oh yeah, I think you're right. I think I turned - - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  The sound down for this.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: - - - because yeah. I' 11 have to get out of this and do it. Might be bugged right now. What's on the agenda for today? "I don't have any plans. How about you?" I'm currently in a tribunal. "No kidding. What</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>were you doing before I interrupted you?" Hoping that I win this tribunal</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-25</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">because they think I'm crazy, but I'm not crazy. "Words can not express my love for you." Yeah.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: All right. Yes, Doctor Drew?</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW: I'm interested in your study history. I did gather you do -you have qualified (indistinct) at University. You've done that over the last- how long?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">IOÂ  MR NESMITH: It took me ten to complete a philosophy degree. But you've got to think that's ten years, most of that was homeless. So, it was difficult to finish a philosophy degree.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  That's what I'm thinking. (indistinct) and I'm wondering how</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>you did it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Yeah. It was hard.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  So, how did you do it?</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: How did I do it? I had to convert all of my - all of the papers, like the books, to text, so I' II show you. Let's say - lets say I get a big fat book, right. This is my text book. So, I would stand there and go</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........: Photograph every page.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  Yeah. No, that's okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  And then I would - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW: So, but you actually-you actually continued to develop new ideas over that time to put in to your - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Of course.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: And you submitted essays, online did you? You had to do all remotely?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Essays online?</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Well, to pass your-to get your degree (indistinct) essays.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Oh, yeah, yeah. Some of it was - I think- some of it was internal, some of it was external, most of it was external. Most of it was</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>external.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHI0S/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-26</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: So, you'd</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  I'd have two - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  be able to do the lectures by podcast or something?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Yeah. Yeah. Usually it was two - each unit had two essays and an exam at the end and the - every once in a while, they would have like a</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>test, like an online test.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Did you have to go down to where ever the Uni is it do the tests> MR NESMITH: No. They have points - I would have been able - ifI was</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>here and I was still studying at Murdoch then they would send the exams to the</p><p style="text-align: center;">ANU and then I would have to take the exams at the ANU. MS..........: (indistinct) ANU. Oh, that's handy.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  So, when did you graduate? It was just this year, was it?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: At the beginning of this year. I finished everything in November, that when the semester ended but it takes them a while to do - so at the beginning of the year obviously you graduate. I think it was actually</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Australia Day. I think that's the day I officially graduated.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Can I ask you, this is a - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Go for it.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: - - - personal question but how doctor O'Neil described how you seemed to feel when you were brought here at the beginning of your stay. You were brought here involuntarily. She's described that you were very upset. You fluctuated between crying and laughing and angry and that's not</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>how you are now.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: What she was talking about, I don't know about fluctuating between crying, okay. What the - she took it out of context. The only time that I cried was when they refused to give me back my phone. So, I got on my</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>knees and I said, "Please give me back my phone." "Please give me back my phone." because my psychology is augmented into this phone. I have - I have created documentaries that are over 1,200 hours. Think- Think about that. Think about how - how much time 1,200 hours is. And I know you say Oh I create short films, but I do not create short films. I create long films. And the</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>thing is, these films are not amateur because I took philosophy of film which</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">has a protasis, an epitasis and a catastrophe which is the format for any filming. My psychology is augmented into the internet and whenever this is taken away from me, my mind starts to go because my memories are here. I keep my memories here. And every time I need to check on something - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: It's very upsetting for people and there are a lot of studies about how people are changing the way they think because of our reliance on smart phones. We use them for our short memory. We don't learn things anymore, so I can totally understand - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: But I learn things through it, but the thing is that is that I need that reference. I feel like this is like my secondary memory.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  I understand. But I want to ask you a question, do you feel that</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>the medication that you've had which effectively, was these injections of say Olanzapine and the treating team would like you to continue doing that every two weeks and then moving up to every month. Do you think that you're able to think creatively and intellectually and philosophically now even though you've had some medication? You seem okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Of course. Its' just difficult. It's like there's a wall or a veil. MS DANIEL: A veil.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MR NESMITH: - - - a veil that I-where that veil's when I'm not on medication, that veils gone, and I can see straight. I can see clearly. When I'm on any anti-psychotics it's like there's a veil. But to be honest, I've finished my work as in I finished the video component of my work and now it's my website linking all those videos.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Yep.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: So, it-it Idon't need that creativity so much now anymore but - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: So, what's your view about taking - being discharged from here in a week or two and then going - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Please say yeah. Please say yeah.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Well, I- we don't have much control over that but then they would- the doctors recommend that you stay in contact with City Mental Health every two weeks to start off with, to have an injection and the moving probably to every month.</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Why injection? I hate needles like needles I really, really hate needles.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Probably because they thought- - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  You're not answering the question. The question is - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Well, are you sayingtbat you'd be happy to take oral medication.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Yes ma'am.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  You need to reliably take it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  I would. I promise.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Yeah. What went wrong or what happened with he three other hospitals you went to. Do you know why they discharged you, or was it on the basis that you have treatment? (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: They just, yes it was only Olanzapine too but the only reason that I could not continue with Olanzapine because when I moved to the US, they were really, really expensive. It was like $3,000 per month, that they wanted me to pay for the medication and I could not do that.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: No. So, you'd be happy to have Olanzapine orally? MR NESMITH: That would be good. Yes, ma'am.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR DREW:Â  What's your current thought about the Masonic Lodge?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: It's in the past now because I've already done that work. You know I never even went there so.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR DREW:Â  You're not worried about them anymore?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  No, sir.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  They're not going to ruin the world?</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: They're not going to ruin tbe world? I don't know, they probably will but it's not my fault.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  You're not worried about that anymore?</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-29</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Well, I did what I did - I did everything I could to try to save it and that's it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  So, who - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  By making your documentaries?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Hm'mm. That's how I did it. And I can do lots of things. Like I don't have to - I never even been to their lodge. But I made a</p><p style="text-align: center;">IO<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>documentary where - because what happened, I split the Freemasons because - does anybody know the story of Pigmania(?).</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  Yeah.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MR NESMITH: That's true Freemasonry, which is to - basically, they're building like that - the perfect woman right, they're thinking of that perfect woman and trying to chisel away but really, they're chiselling at the own heart but then, through that process they find the perfect soul mate, right. And that's what Freemasonry started out as ,but they lost their origins. So, now I am - just</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>like I am the leader of the Illuminati, I this (indistinct) I split the Illuminati and lots of the Illuminati followed me. I did the same thing to the Freemasons now. So, I'm the leader of the Freemasons, or I split it, so some are some aren't.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........: How did you split it?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Divide and conquer. It really works. It really works. What you've got to do is you got to get the people that-you got to encourage the people -you got to show the light -you got to show how -what I'm doing is</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>way better than what they're doing.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: And do you think you can show that by having your material available on the web?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  Yes, ma'am. Yes, ma'am. Most definitely.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Okay. All right so - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  Did doctor Les have any more questions?</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Doctor Les, do you have any more questions? MR DREW: No, I haven't (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........: All right. Ms Banks did you want to - is there anything else Mr</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHIOS/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-30</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Nesmith needs to tell us or you that you need to ask him to tell us? Any questions that you have for him</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  No. Not at this stage. It think we've had a long chat yesterday</p><p style="text-align: center;">5Â  and a brief chat this morning, so I think I do have some instructions here - you've pretty much covered most of the things that we talked about but in terms of the legislative issues I think I can hone in a little bit more if that's possible.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MR NESMITH: I'm not aggressive and I'm not violent and I live a beautiful life. I love the life that I live. And I would not trade it any other life and I really pray that you don't try to make me live a life that isn't-that isn't compatible with y psychology because that's when - that's when I' II be -</p><p style="text-align: center;">(<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>you'll be hurting me if you do that. I'm happy being eccentric. I like who I</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>am, and I like my role in this world which I crafted, and I really hope that you</p><p style="text-align: center;">can dismiss this order and let me on my own free will take the treatment that you provide me. In my own free will because I will. I will.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Ms Halsey, would you have any questions for Mr Nesmith?</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HASLEY: No, I spent a lot of time with Wendell yesterday afternoon, didn't we? We had a good chat. He read me some of his material. I had a look at some of his videos. He's got a couple of books published. He spent ten years building up this body of knowledge that he has on the internet, and on his</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>website that he's making available for other people. I think, you know, he -he consistently- consistently professed his pacifist nature. That he's you know, not aggressive. He's not going to hurt anybody. There's no risks in that. I'm probably a little bit biased towards Mr Nesmith's way of life because I have arm of my own family that's very similar to this. Somebody who is the same</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>age that also studied philosophy and also is a little bit left of centre and doesn't sort of fit within society norms. He's fabulous. I could spend hours - I could spend days with him. I could spend weeks with him. You know, he doesn't live in the same world as I live in and obviously you know the intellect is sort of way above what I can comprehend. And I think we do have an awesome</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>intellect here and something that you know I think would be doing a disservice if we dulled that and tried to control that too much. And that is my concern. I think, you know, he's living a good life. I think he's a very good person. His intentions are good. Yes, it may not be you know, what we think is the norm. And there may be some mental illness there, but I think we have to so1t of</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>establish whether he is refusing any treatment for that and I don't think he is. Whether he is a risk to himself, and others, and I'm not sure that we've established that either. I just have some concerns that you know, we have a remarkable human being here who's done a lot of work. A lot of University study and I just wouldn't like to dull that, and control that. That's all I have to</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>say. Thank you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHl 08/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-31</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: All right. Well, we might go back and just ask Doctor O'Neil or Mr Thomas if they wanted to summarise the situation from their point of view and then we'll ask Ms Banlcs to finish for us.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW: I want to go first,(indistinct) what means of order did you have in mind?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: That's a difficult question because we didn't submit the</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>application, or the order, I guess.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  (indistinct) context. You've seen him for (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Yeah, about a week and a half.</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  A week and a half.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS O'NEIL: I mean, in order to establish the injections over a period of a few months - I mean I guess a few months would be a good starting point. That</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>way he could have his next injection in a fortnight, another one a month after that, and hopefully he would be doing well at that stage.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  So, three months?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS O'NEIL: I thinlc three months would be a good - a good idea. To just really have a good period of stable (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  Observation.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: Mr Thomas, did you have any further comments of what we should think about when we get to go and have a talk about what to decide?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: I guess just from a community perspective my concern is at the moment, acknowledging the huge change in Mr Nesmith's changed metal</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>state on treatment. I agree with the doctors that there's been a substantial change from my engagements with him. I guess my concern from this point of view is acknowledging that Mr Nesmith's not saying he's violent at this current point in time but just bring to light the fact that he was irate in the Centrelink and that required the APP to be called and to be handcuffed due to his</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>delusional beliefs wanting to access forms allowing him to defy God when the forms - when advised they didn't exist demanding - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Last time I went to Medicare - I'd like to stop you there.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR THOMAS:Â  No, that's okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-32</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: I asked, cause I was very cross with them, I asked who I could complain to and they said I could only complain online. And I said I want a form to complain on - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS:Â  Yep.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: - - - and I'm not leaving her until you give me a form.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10Â  Â MR THOMAS:Â  So, the form - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: So, I sat down, and I waited and eventually somebody came, and they won't give you a form to complain on, in writing, to a real person.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15Â  Â MS..........:Â  Yep.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: You're obliged to go and do something online. It's infuriating. IfI'd been a man, I have no doubt, someone would have gone we don't have time for this woman - man, let's just call the police and they can put the</p><p style="text-align: center;">20Â  Â handcuffs on.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS:Â  Yep, so the form - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  So, I don't</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS:Â  No, that's okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: I- you may think this guy was brought in in handcuffs, but it doesn't necessarily mean he was (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: No, I have - I spoke with the police that was there back when the time - the form that Mr Nesmith wanted was the form that was advising him to defy God and there's no form that exists for that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........: That might have been his summaiy of the form.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS:Â  That was his words and they explained that to him.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  Why would he have to be handcuffed?</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: Because he pushed through the police after he was advised that they were going to wait for the mental health to come and speak with him and when he- - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........: Hepushed through the police to leave?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: He pushed- no, to get back into Centrelink to get this form. So, he actually pushed through them to get through the doors to get into Centrelink, and he wasn't handcuffed until that point. When he's actually and</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>physically came into contact the police and they believe he was also speaking about he if doesn't get the form - I spoke with an officer by the name of Katie, who advised that he would blow up bridges and referred to it as a metaphor to get this form. So, that's my concern.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">IO<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........: That's - if -and he said he would blow bridges but that that was a metaphor?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: Ina metaphor term but he's also spoken about engaging iu hand to hand combat with people part of the Freemasons so - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Do you think the police know what a metaphor is?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: I think they do but they had enough concern to bring him in with that.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  Iknow it sounds (indistinct) it doesn't - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: But the form - but I guess my principle that I'm trying to emphasise is the form that he needed didn't exist, advised that it didn't exist,</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>wanting to videotape people</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR DREW:Â  It couldn't possibly be in existence.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS:Â  Yeah. So, I think his rational for becoming upset - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Well, he might have been speaking about a (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: So, I've been upset with Centrelink myself and I guess being upset over something that doesn't exist and trying to explain is different to</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>being upset about processes and principles to being upset about something that's based on delusional and doesn't exist. That's my concern.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  Mr Nesmith what was the form?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MR NESMITH:Â  It was not a form, that's why- I don't understand it. There's' so many lies in this and you just assume the lies are truth. Okay, what happened was I went into Centrelink to tell them - to ask about artificial intelligence, that needs to be where my job is right because God has commanded me to invest everything into artificial intelligence because if we</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>release artificial intelligence with out a moral framework then it's going to start</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-34</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">destroying us. It's going to start killing us because we're not logical creatures because we do stuff like this and it makes no sense because all I'm trying to do is save the world and I'm getting into trouble for trying to save the world. So, I need to be - I need a job that's in artificial intelligence. So, I went to</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>Centrelink and told them that- that because Salvation Army (indistinct) said that I'd just take any job.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Have you done nay work in computer science? Have you got any sort of experience in coding?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Yeah, yeah. I code, I'm a programmer.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Do you know how to code? So, you've got a degree in coding</p><p style="text-align: center;">(<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>or?</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: No, but I have two - I have a certificate two in information technology and I have a diploma in PC repair and I have a diploma in Java programming.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  He has a fairly- fairly extensive website.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  And so - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Cause this is the future, artificial intelligence. MR NESMITH:<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>It is.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: We will be replaced very soon - - - MR NESMITH: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  - - - with artificial decision making technology.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: And do you want it to have more framework? MS DANIEL: That's a-this is the big issue.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH: See, that's my big issue. That's why God is telling me - because I know how to do it right. That's why God is telling me I have to do this in artificial intelligence. They just want me to get any job. Like a McDonaldsjob or something like that but I can't do that. God's saying, because I'm best - I'm the best person to be able to implement this because I</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>spent my whole life doing it. I can't go and get a McDonalds job. So, they</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHI0S/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-35</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">told me to go to Centrelink. So, I went to Centrelink; I talked to the guy about it and he said that under your situation - he gave me a few papers and stuff - he said under your situation, you will have to defy God in order to continue to receive our payments.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Well, that sounds sensible. I'm sure God will be in with that because if you have to get income in order to progress to get the job in artificial intelligence, then you're going to have to work at Macca's or somewhere, for the short term.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: But it's not logical because what happens when - what happens if it happens in six months and I'm not - I need to be working in artificial intelligence.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  But you've got to do it step by step.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: But step by step is spending the last ten years working on the software. This is an operating system that I've created for artificial intelligence.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: Have you worked in IT before Mr Nesmith? MRNESMITH: Yes,ma'am.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS..........: Have you been in paid employment in IT?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Yes, ma' am.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  Where?</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........:Â  Who for?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Royal Flying Doctors Service, Beckers, Amtec, Netway Internet, Netway Computers, many more. A lot more.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS..........: So, that was in America was it?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: No, those are all in Australia but there is Computer Plus that's in America, and then there is - there's another computer place that was in</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>America too. But what happened is I - because they told me straight out that their systems are - under my conditions, their system is making me defy God. So I said, "Can I please have that in writing?" And they said - they said, "No, no, we're not going to write that." And I said, "Then can I please film you saying that?" And then they said, "No, no, no." And then I said, "Well, then</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>we have a problem." I never got irate, I never got upset, I never raised my</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-36</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">voice, right. I said, "Okay, then I'm not - look you said it to me. I'm not going to leave until I get some type of confirmation for this, right." So eventually they turned on the alarms, called the police and told me to go sit over there quietly, which I did. And then when the police came, they took me outside and</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>- and then the police were trying to stay - leave. They want you to leave, so leave. And I said, "I can't leave until I get that bit of information that - because they told me that their systems are causing me to defy God and I need to get that information so I can then publicly release it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">IO<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS DANIEL: So do you understand that to - that what - that explanation that you've just given sounds completely - completely strange and unreal and delusional to your ordinary police officer on the street? Do you - are you able to understand from the AFP Police officer's point of view, that explanation is really out there.</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Do you see that?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  Well, I - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Can you see his perspective?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Well, my perspective is that - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: No. Can you see his? MR NESMITH: Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  Can you see - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Yeah, I think that's - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  - - - from the police officer - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Everybody - but there's so many systems in this world that cause you to defy God and - and if - and if I could get the evidence and publicly release that, then that shows how terrible the system is because it's directly causing you to defy God.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Yeah. And that makes sense to you, but that doesn't make sense to the police officer who's just been called out on a job because some bloke's causing havoc at Centrelink and we don't understand it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  And see what happened was because I wanted it in writing</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">and they said - I didn't push through police, I just - but they - what happened was they said - they said, "We'll arrest you if you go back in."</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Yeah.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: And - - - MS DANIEL: And - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MR NESMITH: But they were trying to get me to go away. They were like, "Just leave, just leave." And - and I said, "But I need that documentation." And they - they said, "The only way you're getting that documentation is if you back in because then we'll have to write a police report." So I started to walk back in and then they - they both attacked me and - and then handcuffed</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>me, right. And then there's where the story is. I didn't push through police officers, I just started to walk back in, and the thing is, I didn't even get in before I was tackled to the ground and my face smashed against the wall.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Righto. I can understand so clearly how that all unravelled. So</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>thank you for that Mr Nesmith. Ms Banks, do you want to finish our hearing today by summing up the position from Mr Nesmith's point of view on what he submits we should do?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  Yes. So as indicated at the beginning, the making of a</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>psychiatric treatment order is opposed. Obviously Mr Nesmith does not want one. He has made that very clear but from a legal point of view, in my submission, the questions of refusal and the questions of risk of harm to self or others there's not enough evidence to make those out. Mr Nesmith is clearly quite passionate and he's made it very clear that he loves life and he enjoys the</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>way that he lives. Obviously he lives in a world that doesn't quite understand the way that he lives and this has somewhat of a disabling effect on him in some ways and I think he's just given a perfect example of that with his experience at Centrelink and president, as you noted, it's very unlikely that the police would have understood the situation. Miscommunication and I imagine</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>that this is something that Mr Nesmith potentially comes across in his daily life, having to deal with agencies and bodies that don't think the same way that he does.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">When it comes to the question of refusal, Mr Nesmith has already indicated</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>that he's happy to continue taking medication and indeed that was his instructions to me. He will continue to take the medication, regardless of whether an order is in place. In particular, he really likes to have contact with City Mental Health and he says that he had a worker there called Karina for quite a while. He used to visit her once or twice a week and he said she - their</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>relationship was very therapeutic. He would like to continue in a relationship</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">like that and re-engage with City Mental Health if possible. These two things can be done without an order in place, based on the instructions that</p><p style="text-align: center;">Mr Nesmith has given. In regards to risk of harm to self or others, or deterioration, in my view, and I concur with Chris on this, this criteria hasn't</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>been made out. Based on the evidence in the application and on the evidence that has been given, there's -there's postulation of potential risks but there's no evidence or history to suggest that risk of harm to others or any kind of violence is - is a real problem.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Even in this incident that happened at Centrelink, it doesn't appear as though there was any violence or aggression. There's probably misunderstanding and probably some kind of - I imagine that you were quite distressed at the time but that doesn't mean that it's a risk to other people and arguably, given the - the length of history here, given that Mr Nesmith had contact back in 2012 and</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>2013, for that period of time for there to be no evidence of violence or aggression, or confronting people about these - his system of beliefs, I would argue that there's - there's ce1tainly not enough there to reach that threshold for you to be satisfied that he is going to cause a risk to others. In terms of risk to self, he's already explained that he feels quite fit and healthy. He gets food.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>He lives quite a good lifestyle. He stays clean. He enjoys nature obviously and enjoys bushwalking and looking after himself and it - at this stage, I would argue there's not enough evidence to suggest that there's a risk of harm to himself.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>In regards to the deterioration, again, there's no evidence to suggest that there's been a deterioration and we don't know if this has been his mental state the entire time and - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  That is not the question. The question is, whether because of</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>his illness, he's likely to suffer serious deterioration in his mental state and functioning.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS: Yes. There's no history to suggest that there is a risk of deterioration.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: There's evidence from Dr O'Neil of what the prognosis is, if untreated.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  There's four admissions to the hospital, to other hospitals.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANK.S: But we don't know if that was voluntary, we don't know what the - the nature of the admissions were interstate. We do know that the</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>previous admission to Canberra Hospital was what I would argue is</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">misadventure and he was not kept for long at that stage. The previous one, there was concern from the GP but he hasn't been kept for - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  There was - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  - - - a long period of time.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BANKS: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(indistinct) for a psychiatric treatment order.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  And it was not made.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  Yes. Yeah, we don't !mow the reason it wasn't -well, I don't</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>know the reason it wasn't made on the previous occasion but obviously there - there was some - the criteria were not met for making the order. He's - he's obviously held this system of beliefs for a long time and the work that he's been doing has been over the past 10 years. He's been doing his philosophy degree for the last 10 years. He's obviously a thinker.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  If he'd been well, he might've got it done in three.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS: I know people who are well who get it done in 10 years, so I mean it's just - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: If he'd been well though (indistinct) wouldn't have been homeless.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  He may have - yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: If he'd been well, his mental state and functioning would've been - if he'd been treated, his mental state and functioning might've been more optimal and he would've still had all of his passion for nature and for intellectual engagement in these new technologies and all of that. He wouldn't</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>have been distracted by delusional thought content.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS: That's - that's assuming that it is delusional thought content and that there is an illness.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: So you think that this stuff about the Masons and the child sacrifice is not delusional?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  I'm not a doctor; I'm a lawyer.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  And I'm acting on - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  No, no, no - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  I'm acting on instructions.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: No, you can't get away with it like that. Do you think it sounds realistic? You don't have to be a doctor - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Does Mr Nesmith on instructions tell us that that's the situation?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  Yes. That's his views. Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  That's his view.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANl(S: Absolutely. He's made that very clear to the tribunal this morning.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: It's not a view, it's a belief. MS DANIEL: It's a belief, yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BANKS:Â  Well, yes belief. I have already said system of beliefs. I'm not</p><p style="text-align: center;">- I'm not trying - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  But do you think it's a realistic - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BANKS:Â  - - - to step away from that?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Her view is not important.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  Yeah. It's really- - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>(indistinct) Mr Nesmith.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  That's not appropriate for me to put my view forward.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  In - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  So obviously my concern is that Mr Nesmith's life has been</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>lost to him.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  He - he's happy.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  He's perfectly happy.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS: He's happy. He's - - - MS DANIEL:Â  He's perfectly happy.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS BANKS: He enjoys his lifestyle and - - - MS DANIEL: He could've been professor - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  - - - there are - I mean that's us - that's us - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  In a tent. He could still be in a tent but be a professor.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  That's us thinking that being a professor is a good thing. I mean that's - that's something that you work towards and again, this is corning</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>in to the social construct of our idea of what is normal and what people strive towards and what they should be doing, if they have this intelligence.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: That's true. On his own submission to us, he wants to save the world and he's going to do probably a better job of that if he's able to</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>promulgate his beliefs and lecture and all of that, than creating a website, which I' rn not even sure is functional.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS: It is.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  It is.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: It is.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  Yes, absolutely.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: But I don't - I am a professor because every single second of every single day there's about between four and 600 people that are watching my videos.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  Mrn'hrn.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: So right now, maybe there's 400 people watching my videos. In an hour, maybe there'll be 525 people watching my videos. I am a professor, I'm just an online professor and - and I don't see any need for me to</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>go and be a professor in a real - in a real school, a real university because I'm</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-42</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">doing it all online and I'm - I'm giving it away for free too, because that's what I think a real education is. I love - I love my fans so much that I want to give them, away all that - that's in my heart, in my head, to them for free and I'm trying to work a way to make it donations based. But the platform had to be</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>completely created before - before it was - before I was able to do that. So soon there will be donations and hopefully I can get these donations to then support me, so I' II no longer require Centrelink assistance.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Can I ask you a question about your willingness to take tablets. MR NESMITH: Yes, ma'am.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  If you're willing to take tablets, why haven't you been doing</p><p style="text-align: center;">Â  Â  Â that in all your interactions with City Mental Health over the last couple of I5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>years? I presume they've been suggesting to you that you take tablets.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  I was in Mexico.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  He only returned - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  I just got back - I just got back from Mexico.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: But what about when you were in Lismore and Ballarat and Cairns, because you have indicated that you've taken a range of</p><p style="text-align: center;">anti-psychotics.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: I think you've given us some views. MR NESMITH: Olanzapine's been the best.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: Yes. So after each admission, when you've gone away from the hospital, have they given you medication - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  I continue - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL:Â  - - - to take?</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I always continued, yes. That's the only reason - - - MS DANIEL: But how did you reappear to the - I mean you've clearly</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>brought yourself to the attention of other people in order to be admitted to</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHI0S/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-43</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">hospitals. So how did you get in to Lismore Hospital? What happened there? Briefly.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Lismore Hospital.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Or Cairns or Ballarat? One of them? What happened to get you back into the hospital?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Making films that are controversial. My films are</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>controversial.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: All right. I think we might just adjourn and have a conversation. Now you're free to stay here of course and chat amongst yourselves but remember the microphone's still recording us. So don't say</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>anything you don't want someone to hear.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Thank you very much. And please, I'll be - I'll be really good. If you don't put an order on me, I'll be really good and I'll take my meds and I'll have contact.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ADJOURNED RESUMED</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">[11.02AM]</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">[11.04AM]</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS DANIEL: All right. Well, we're resuming matter MH108 of 2012. The tribunal is not going to decide this application today. We're going to adjourn the application and we would like more evidence from the applicant. It might be from Dr O'Neil but I think that what might happen is if we adjourn this matter for three weeks, that would give Mr Thomas, City Mental Health an</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>oppmtunity to make contact with Ballarat - - - MR THOMAS: Yeah.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  - - - Cairns and Lismore Hospitals and obtain for us a full</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>medical history for Mr Nesmith. IfI could give everyone, for your assistance, a summary of where we're at, we do believe that Mr Nesmith has a mental illness and that there is treatment that is recommended for that. We are concerned about this question of risk of harm to self or others and the question of mental deterioration and we think that the longer term medical history will</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>give us some idea of what side of the line Mr Nesmith's case falls on. So I can't tell you the exact date that we're adjourning the matter to, until I go back to the tribunal and get the date that this tribunal is sitting again. Does that make sense? Because we've heard so much and we need to go part-hard on this hearing and finish on probably a Thursday afternoon, hopefully in about</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>three weeks. Does that make sense everyone.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 12.07.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-44</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Yeah.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  All right. So what will happen for you, Mr Nesmith is you're</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>currently in hospital under a detention order and that order I think requires you to stay in hospital for potentially up to 18 July. So you will continue - that doesn't mean that you will stay here until 18 July, you will be talking with the treating team about when they think you're ready for discharge.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  I have a lot of work to do and I would really appreciate it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Yeah. So this is not a decision that this tribunal makes. This is a decision that the treating team make - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: - - - when to discharge you. At the moment they have authority to hold you here, even if you wanted to discharge yourself, until 18 July. But they might decide that you're right to go home earlier. Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Okay. Thank you very much.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Can I ask, what's being done about Mr Nesmith's possessions? Because they're on the side of a hill at the moment, aren't they? Your tent and</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>your swag.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Mm'hm.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  So is anyone doing anything to make sure no-one goes and</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>scavenges them?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR THOMAS: Mr Nesmith hasn't actually (indistinct) to us where he stays, so we're unable to - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  But you wouldn't - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Are they safe where they are?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  No-one would be able to find it.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: No, because it's possums would be going through everything.</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Possums.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS: You said that you keep your important papers and whatnot in a locker.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Yeah.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BANKS:Â  At the (indistinct) centre.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS DANIEL: You don't want -that's an expensive swag. You don't want to lose that swag.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DAVIES:Â  And your heater.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS DANIEL: If some human being found it, that's all. All right. So when you get the order, which we will type up and get sent to you this afternoon. It will say these proceedings are adjourned to and then there's a date and a time. It will be an afternoon. It will be potentially not here but in the</p><p style="text-align: center;">City Mental Health building but on level 4. All right.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS STEELE: So I think, if I may interrupt. Mr Nesmith from my perspective, this also gives you the opportunity to take treatment that the doctors are prescribing involuntarily.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  Yeah, I will.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS STEELE: And keep in touch with City Mental Health and reach out to your case worker.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  Yes, I will.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS STEELE: And ask them what they're going to do, so that we have some established history that you are going to take your treatment. Because you're clearly much better now. You're presenting quite well today, than what you</p><p style="text-align: center;">35Â  were on admission. So that's a really important responsibility that you have, and I think the other issue is we don't have an address.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Well - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BANKS: If you could do the hearing notice and send it to me, I' II - - - MS DANIEL: Will you give it?</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS STEELE:Â  Okay. That's great.</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Do you need an address to send mail? Is that what you need?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Longer term we will but at the moment, we'll just send this</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>copy of this order today to Ms Steele and she'll give it to you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL:Â  Print it out and give it to him, so you've got that.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Okay, thank you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>15</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS STEELE: So you need to go find - when you're released, (indistinct) and keep (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR ........: Yeah, so she's only personally - I think the next three weeks after this one, so I'm s01t of helping with Mr Nesmith's case because I was with the review. But as a duty officer, I'm predominantly at the office. So if you present to the reception, you'll be able to ask for me. Ifl'm not there,</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>somebody else will be able to grab these details from you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Okay. Would I be able to get Karina back?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR ........:Â  So Karina actually works for a different team. So Karina works for</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>the access team, which kind of triages - - - MR NESMITH: Did she change?</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR .........:Â  No, see Karina was always (indistinct) that was the access team.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>So somebody who isn't known to us - because you came back from Mexico, you weren't open to a community team, so that team assesses somebody if they need assistance from mental health and it was deemed that you did. So she referred us - you to us, as the community team for longer term care. So Karina just does short term assessments for people, to sort of refer them on to longer</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>term care.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR ........: So she only does brief interactions with people.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS DANIEL: Okay. Well, thank you everyone for coming. It's been a lengthy hearing and we've covered a lot of information. I will see you in</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>approximately three weeks' time.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Thank you very much. Appreciated.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MATTER ADJOURNED AT 11.10 AM ACCORDINGLY</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">TRANSCRIPT OF PROCEEDINGS</p><p style="text-align: center;">Spark & Cannon</p><p style="text-align: center;">Phone:<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>1300 502 819</p><p style="text-align: center;">Email:<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>clientseivices@sparkandcannon.com.au</p><p style="text-align: center;">Web:<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>www.sparkandcannon.com.au</p><p style="text-align: center;">Adelaide I Brisbane I Canberra I Darwin I Hobart I Melbourne I Perth I Sydney</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Copyright in this document is reserved to the Australian Capital Territory. Reproduction of this document (or part thereof, in any format) except with the prior written consent of the attorney-general is prohibited. Please note that under section 43 of the Copyright Act 1968 copyright is not infringed by anything reproduced for the purposes of a judicial proceeding or of a report of a judicial proceeding.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">AUSTRALIAN CAPITAL TERRITORY CIVIL AND ADMINISTRATIVE TRIBUNAL</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL SENIOR MEMBER DR DREW MEMBER DR DAVIES</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">TRANSCRIPT OF PROCEEDINGS MH No 108 of 2012</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">WENDELL CHARLES NESMITH</p><p style="text-align: center;">CONSIDER AN APPLICATION FOR A PSYCHIATRIC ORDER</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">CANBERRA</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">3.36 PM, THURSDAY, 2 AUGUST 2018</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS TRACEY with MS HALSEY from the Public Advocate</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON with MS MABEY from City Mental Health Team MS BATES appeared for Mr Nesmith</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: We have Mr Nesmith's matter. Are you staying for that, Ms Halsey?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY: Yes, staying for that. He's out there.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: He's outside? MS HALSEY: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: We might ask him if he wants to come in. Anywhere is fine so long as you've got a microphone. The ACT Civil and Administrative Tribunal is sitting today to consider an application for a psychiatric treatment order for Wendell Charles Nesmith. This is matter 108 of 2012. We'll just start by all introducing ourselves. I'm presidential member</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Daniel. I'm the presiding member on the tribunal this afternoon.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MEMBER DAVIES: I'm Robyn Davies, community member, hello.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">SENIOR MEMBER DREW: I'm Les Drew, psychiatrist.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: I'm Julie Hanson from the city mental health team. MS MABEY: I'm Kate Mabey from the city mental health team.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH: I'm Wendell Charles Nesmith and I'm a philosopher.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES: Adele Bates, legal aid ACT representing for Mr Nesmith today.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS TRACEY: Penny Tracey from the public advocate.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY: Chris Halsey from the public advocate.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Okay, good. Ms Hanson, I got (indistinct) your last name.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY: Mabey, M-A-B-E-Y.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: You're both from City Mental Health?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS MABEY: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: I think the last time we were all together a couple of weeks ago we were at the adult mental health unit. Mr Nesmith was there for a short while and on that occasion I think Mr Ke! Thomas- - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: He's from your team. He's on leave.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON: He's on leave, yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So he came and Mr Nesmith was there and Ms Bates you were there too, weren't you ?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BATES: Iwas,yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Ms Halsey was there?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So for the record I' II just summarise where we got to on that occasion. The tribunal had heard a lot of evidence but we had a couple of questions in our mind. The first was, was Mr Nesmith going to refuse treatment upon discharge from hospital. He said he wasn't</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>going to and we didn't know when he was going to be discharged even at that stage. The second issue was that the treating team said to us look, what is the risk for Mr Nesmith if he doesn't have appropriate treatment and when we asked that question they said he's had actually multiple admissions and so he's obviously coming into contact with the public or the authorities or something.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">He's been admitted several times in other places so we don't know anything about that but we say that it means that he is at risk. He's vulnerable or something and so we said in the adjournment period the treating team could perhaps chase up for us information about these other admissions as well as</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>giving Mr Nesmith in the adjournment period, he will have been discharged, he can get back to his life and he can then come back and talk to us about what treatment has been recommended for him after discharge and what's his view about that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>Those I think were the two factors that we wanted to hear about today. I wonder, I might ask maybe Ms Hanson or Ms Mabey one of you perhaps as the treating team to start by updating us on Mr Nesmith's discharge from hospital and what the plan for his treatment is going forward. Is there a need for treatment going forward?</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY: Mr Nesmith was reviewed by Dr Flynn who did the original report prior to his admission. He was reviewed on- - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: The 31st.</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-3</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: The 31st.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: That's only this week.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH: Yes, two days ago.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Yes. Her impression is that he is agreeable to treatment however it's been explained that it's more, it's sort of the lesser of two evils. It's really to avoid having to go back to hospital.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: What is the recommended treatment? I mean three weeks ago it was we think you should stay in hospital for a couple more days. So that's not the situation anymore?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON: No. I believe it's to continue with the medication.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: What's that medication?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: At the moment he's on Olanzapine.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Is that a tablet? MS HANSON: No, he's on a depo injection.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: How often is that?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Fortnightly.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: What else is part of the treatment plan?</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: It says here that he's actually also on some oral medication as well. That's now changed. So to continue engagement with Dr Flynn. I think the plan was also that we were going to help him with some housing.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: I' II stop you there. When people say continue engagement with Dr Flynn or mental health, that's just, to me that's just waffle. No person (indistinct) but it's like a summary. What I really want to know is who has he got to see and when? How often?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON: He's got to see - - - PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Dr Flynn.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Yes, Dr Flynn.</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHl 08/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-4</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: How often?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: I'm just having a look at her last report when she says her, when she next wants to see him. Can I ask Mr Nesmith did she make another</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>appointment?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: No, we haven't but Dr Flynn says she wants to see me probably about monthly but Kel's probably weekly but we'II probably change to go it fortnightly. That's what they were saying which is good for me.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Ke! weekly for the moment and then move to fortnightly.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Mr Thomas is currently our duty officer and Mr Nesmith has</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>been assigned a clinical manager and she's currently on leave.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Okay, so Ke! will keep in touch with</p><p style="text-align: center;">Mr Nesmith until she gets back.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: And then there will be a handover?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So Ke!, weekly at the moment. MS HANSON: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Okay, and then moving to fortnightly and the new case manager will come in.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MEMBER DAVIES: Can I take you back to the meds? Olanzapine depo fmtnightly.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Fortnightly, yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MEMBER DAVIES: Then are you reading the report of the 31st that talks about oral meds?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: It did say oral medication but my understanding is that that has now been ceased. He was given seven days' supply on discharge and then</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>commenced the fortnightly injection.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-5</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MEMBER DAVIES: So that's the transitional oral meds until the depo kicks m.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON: That's right.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MEMBER DAVIES: All right, thank you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Â  Â  Â PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So we got an email, so what we have IO<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>before us is this. We had the original report application that we had at the hospital three weeks ago and then today we got an email from the tribunal</p><p style="text-align: center;">liaison officer saying that they had received hospital notes from Ballarat and Cairns hospitals. Please advise if you want these emailed to you and I said yes and we've got those but we can barely read them but they're better than</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>nothing and then there's a summary here from the tribunal liaison officer. I'll read this to you because I don't think it's been copied to you at legal aid.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Ms Bates. It's all positive.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell has been engaging with city mental health, accepting</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>treatment and psychiatric review to avoid 'ji1rther torture' i.e. going back to hospital. I'm sure the case manager will attend to the hearing and provide the tribunal with fi1rther information as requested. After psychiatric review on 31 July 2018 "remains very fixed around his beliefs but seems less driven than prior to</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>hospitalisation. Very grandiose, no insight that he has a psychotic illness, is agreeing have farther treatment because of fears of further torture, e.g. going back to hospital. Engagement will continue to be fraught with this tension but currently was able to establish good rapport today. The ongoing plan - continue</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>Olanzapine depo, consider dose increase (indistinct) arrange new GP at the interchange.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">So you need a new GP?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH: Yes; but they won't take new patients right now.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: The interchange practice?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR SHORT:Â  Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: "Needs to start process ofDSP". I think that's disability support pension?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Housing support, need to explore all emergency temporary housing</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>options. Centre/ink certificate dated until mid-October.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHIOS/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-6</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Diagnosis schizophrenia. See scanned copy. Case manager to look into psychological and other support.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">I suppose Centrelink likes there to be a diagnosis on their certificates.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: There has to be a diagnosis.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Hence that because I understand</p><p style="text-align: center;">Mr Nesmith you might disagree with that word of schizophrenia but it may be</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>what Centrelink needs to receive on the certificate to start paying you DSP.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">C<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>15</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR SHORT: It's okay, it's a type of personality disorder, it's pretty close to schizophrenia anyway. I just don't hear voices or don't see things that aren't there.</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Okay, so it's not too far from - - - MR NESMITH: They're both schiz.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: - - -what you'd accept. Yes, they're both schiz.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I'm still schizo no matter how you look at it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: If you want to have a label you can have that label, yes. All right, so that's a document we have. I'm going to ask a copy of that to get made for Ms Bates and Mr Nesmith just so your file is complete.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MSBATES: Thankyou.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: But there's no information in there that wasn't, I've written on that so you'll have to get a copy off - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HALSEY: Can we have a copy of that please, president?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: You haven't got a copy either, Ms Halsey?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY: No, no.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Can you just get another copy printed out? Make two copies, one for Ms Halsey and one for Ms Bates. Thank you. That then updates us on the hÂ·eatment plan, thank you Ms Hanson. That's, I think, complete. Is there anything else on the treatment plan, Dr Drew?</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-7</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">SENIOR MEMBER DREW: Not about the treatment plan but about the attitude towards the plan. Sorry, who was the psychiatrist?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Dr Flynn.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY: Dr Carolyn Flynn.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">SENIOR MEMBER DREW: Right, okay. Is she a psychiatrist?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS MABEY: She's a registrar.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: She's a registrar.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">SENIOR MEMBER DREW: What I would have liked to know is her attitude</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>towards whether or not a PTO was needed.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: What she explained to us just before corning up to hear this is that she felt that it was needed because Mr Nesmith has a history of being itinerant and moving from state to state and has never really engaged with</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>services for a long time to try and improve or I guess make a difference with treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">SENIOR MEMBER DREW: Yes, I would have thought that having a PTO would be encouraging to - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Yes, yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">SENIOR MEMBER DREW: - - - rather than the same. I would have thought ifwe could involve him in treatment on a quasi-voluntary basis so he can still</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>live where he wants to and do what he likes as long as he involves the treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: I think her concern was that, sorry?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS MABEY: He's vulnerable.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Yes, and also the fact that he was only accepting of treatment because it was the lesser of two, you know the sort of two evils to avoid having to go back to hospital and so there was that period he wouldn't engage with</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: I will ask you about that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: That's not true. I actually went there from the beginning on</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>my own free will.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Yes, we pointed that out last time, didn't we?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH: From the beginning right when I got to Canberra I made the appointments. Within the first week that I was in Canberra I was in mental health.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">SENIOR MEMBER DREW: So your position is that you'll continue on this</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>treatment - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Of course, I think it's beneficial.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">SENIOR MEMBER DREW:Â  - - - whether or not you're a PTO.</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Yes, sir, I think it's beneficial for me.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MEMBER DAVIES: That contrasts, Mr Nesmith, with the notes we have from Queensland, in particular where you are taking yourself off oral meds and</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>there's a consistency.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: I might get a copy, I might give my copy of these notes to Ms Bates. It's very hard to read but it does indicate that at points you were like discharged with some oral medication. What happened</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Mr Nesmith?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: The only reason that I stopped taking my medication is because I went to the US and the medication was $600 per month there and I could not afford $600 per month for the medication. I would have stayed on it</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>if it was not for that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MEMBER DAVIES: So these notes do say that in 2016 that you went to the US but in front of me here I've got a psych history that says you were treated with Risperidone in Ballarat in - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Risperidone is bad. No.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MEMBER DAVIES: Canberra in 2013, Lismore 2014 with Olanzapine and that you didn't like those medications.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I don't like Risperidone at all.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MEMBER DAVIES: In fact, you have, there is at page 47, I'm just pointing out that there is precedents here where you have stopped taking medications in</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>the past.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I went from Risperidone to Olanzapine.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Okay. Where did you go to be prescribed</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>the Olanzapine? Was that still in Queensland?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MEMBER DAVIES: It was Lismore according to - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: It was Lismore but I also had it in Queensland too.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">MEMBER DAVIES: He reports that he doesn't like our medications and they make him feel terrible.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Mostly in reference to the Risperidone.</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MEMBER DAVIES: Doesn't believe he needs medication.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY: IfI can just jump in there please president, Wendell has said to me that he would much prefer having a depo injection than having medication</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>because you know, you don't have the risk of forgetting your medication and he said himself that you know, on pills he was forgetting it and he would actually prefer to have depo.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS TRACEY: Can I just say what he has said at the review was that he was</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>resigned to taking medication to please us and to avoid being tortured anymore.</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: You don't want to be taken into hospital. SENIOR MEMBER DREW: My position would be, Wendell, that I'm quite</p><p style="text-align: center;">30Â  convinced by reading all of this material that you do suffer from schizophrenia and that you need treatment and that you ought to be taking this treatment with a treatment order or not.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I agree. I think I should be taking this treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">SENIOR MEMBER DREW: I think you should. It will make your life so much better.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MRNESMITH: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">SENIOR MEMBER DREW: It really will because otherwise you will be tortured all the time because people will just continue taking you back to hospital.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: You don't want that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: When I refer to torture I'm talking, I'm referring to the hospital specifically. I'm not talking about anything outside of the hospital, sir.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5Â  SENIOR MEMBER DREW: No, no. It's also if you don't take, if you do have treatment continuing you will be much more productive than you are. Really productive.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I agree. I agree.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So I guess we now understand that the proposed treatment plan is going forward, and we understand the concerns that Dr Flynn has, that - and we've got - read through the notes that we can read.</p><p style="text-align: center;">We understand that there's a history of falling out of treatment, and some of</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>that is because of the medication being too expensive while he was overseas, some of it is around - it was actually - there was times where the medication prescribed to you did not work for you as well.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">So for whatever reason there's been a failure to get adequate treatment, or</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>engage with adequate treatment in the past. I might just ask Ms BATES first. Ms BATES, do you have any questions for Ms Hanson about the proposed treatment, engagement with treatment, acceptance of treatment, anything on this topic?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS BATES: Thank you. Despite the reasoning for engagement in treatment, has Wendell been engaging since he was released (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  So he did come to the review, yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BATES: He has presented (indistinct) MS HANSON: Yes, he did.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES: Just to clarify- - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: I think that did take quite a number of - like, we did actually have to spend some time locating him. His phone was not working, was not accepting incoming calls.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  You had the wrong number.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  I came in - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-11</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Yes, when we contacted</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  It was apparently, like, an hour after you called.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BATES:Â  Is the plan to move to (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Well, that will be dependent on whether this - you know, medication does work for him. This is a fortnightly medication. However, on a higher dose it can be changed to a monthly injection, yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES:Â  This is a better print.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  I don't need a copy.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DREW:Â  You don't need a copy?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  No.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES:Â  This is (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Yes. This is a better print-out, Ms l;lATES, than the one I gave you. It's much more readable.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  It couldn't be worse.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: It couldn't. Ms Halsey, did you have any questions for Ms Hanson on the topic of treatment plans, and treatment engagement?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HALSEY: As you're probably aware I've been keeping in fairly close contact with Wendell, and meeting up with him, and involved in the housing applications and that sort of thing. Now, I understand that he was allocated a case manager, Nakem. But Nakem is on leave currently, so Ke! has taken over. Ke! is who Wendell thought was his case manager, but I understand that Ke! is</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>the duty manager that's just been - - - MS HANSON: Yes, standing in. Yeah.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  But the last - I know that the last few days Ke! hasn't been at</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>work either.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  No, Ke! hasn't been there either.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  So there hasn't actually been a case manager for Wendell to</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>connect with, but he has tried. I mean, he's been taking paperwork in that sort</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MFII0S/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-12</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ofthing.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Yes. We did receive his housing application yesterday. It</p><p style="text-align: center;">was yesterday, wasn't it, that you dropped it in? We've got a support officer</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>that will be actually also working with Mr Nesmith to get that lodged.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  And the DSP, that sort of thing?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Yes. I think Dr Flynn is going to do a supporting letter in</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>relation to the housing.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY: Good. I'm happy to do a supporting letter for the housing as well. But I thought that when I was talking to Kate - when I was talking to you the other day, Kate, that the housing application had already been done, and it</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>just needed - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: It had been given.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  - - - the bank statements, and the 100 points.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Yes, we I think we were waiting from my instructors on the 100 points ID which now we have. So it's just a matter I think of - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  Going into housing.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Yes. I think as (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: That was all into social housing. We still have the regular housing to do, which she's - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  For ACT Housing.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Chris can help me with that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HALSEY: So you know, he has been making - he's been coming into City Mental Health, he's been engaging, he's done his psychiatric review, he's coming for his depot. Quite happy to have the depot, and engage in care treatment and support, and I think that he is really quite committed to staying in Canberra at this stage. He wants ACT Housing.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">He wants secure housing so that he can come down and stop living in his tent. So I think that shows a commitment that he is not going to abscond. He's not going to be itinerant any more. He actually wants to stay here, and he wants to actually do his work here. So I don't think there's - from my point of view I</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>don't think there's any (indistinct) at this stage. I don't think there's a case to be</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">made for refusing it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: Can I just ask- I don't want to be rude in saying this, but is the city mental the best (indistinct) to be involving Wendell?</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Yes, I think we are. Yes. I think we've got - - - MR NESMITH: They're really good.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DREW:Â  I know they're very good but they're also very stretched.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Yes. I think we're working very hard to try and support him. You know, we don't really have a choice at this particular point in time because he is living within our catchment area anyway. You know, that could change.</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  I was thinking about supported accommodation.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Well, the fact that Mr Nesmith is engaging in treatment, so he wouldn't actually meet their criteria. But if that changed, well, then there is</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>that possibility, and that's irrespective of where he lives in Canberra.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  (indistinct) is that going to make any difference?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  I think the concern - my understanding from Dr Flynn is this</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>sort of history of non-engagement or being itinerant, and not actually continuing with treatment on a sort of a long enough basis.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  Sorry, I was looking at it from the opposite end.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: If you want a PTO, you find a - you're obliged to look after it. If</p><p style="text-align: center;">he's not on a PTO, well, he might fall off.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON: Well, that's what my understanding is. That's what's happened in the past back in 2012 when he was sort of lost to (indistinct) the ACT.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  Yes, but that might have been his. fault. I'm concerned it might</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>be your fault.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Well - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  Would you disengage ifhe wasn't on a</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PTO?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHl 08/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-14</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Would we disengage? No. No, we would not.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  I mean, I've he's on a PTO, you've got to actively go out and see</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>him every two weeks.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Yes, we do, but I - you know - well, I believe that we do actively also, you know, support a lot of people who aren't on PTOs. We are very stretched, but - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: I'm not concerned - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Can you tell me - I'm going to ask a procedural - this is an office question. You have a number of open files. Some</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>of them are on people who are voluntary patients. A patient stops coming to see you. When do you close the file?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: There are so many different circumstances or, you know, situations to take into account. If a person is refusing to engage with us then</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>that's completely different. I mean, we will do everything we possibly can based on assessments. We may even look at having to get an assessment order to actually get that person to re-engage. We don't just - we try not to just stop. There's loads of people we don't do that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS MABEY:Â  We try not to do that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  I'm just wondering because - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  We have an MDT process.</p><p style="text-align: center;">(<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>30</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  Well, I want to know what the process is.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: So if somebody was having difficulty engaging with a client, or getting a client to engage with us, we would ask - we would - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: A voluntary client.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: A voluntary client, yes. We would - first of all you might seek some peer support. You might discuss it with the doctor that last</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>reviewed that person. You would take it to an MDT process where - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Joe failed to turn up at his review this week, and I rang and left a message, and he's never called me back?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON:Â  Yes. So we will start, you know, looking at do we go and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHI0S/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-15</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">knock on that person's door? Do we start contacting family? Next of kin? As I said, we will discuss it in a multi-disciplinary team meeting as to how we can engage that person. You know, maybe there's somebody else on the team that has worked with that person in the past, and they might, you know, have some</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>ideas. You know, just continually inviting them in. We don't just - we tend to not just let people just drop off the books.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Then what happens? So you've tried for a month, and the phone calls haven't been replied to, and you've been up to the</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>house, and they've - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: Can I just say in this case. In other cases you might just let it drop.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS HANSON: You do also sometimes have to respect a person's right to - if they're voluntary, to choose to engage with - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  That's what I'm interested in.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON:Â  We do have to respect that, and we do.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So you have a patient with mental health because you think they've got a mental illness which is being treated by medication and monitoring. They cease taking the medication, they cease</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>engaging in monitoring, and yet sometimes it seems to me files just get closed, whereas I would have thought that all of that background information, if you know someone has a mental illness which leave them at risk of misadventure, or neglect, or whatever, and they cease engaging with their treatment and with their monitoring, wouldn't that mean you should apply for an assessment</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>order?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Every case is an individual, and I can't answer that question based on everybody who ceases engagement with the city mental health team. You know, I think we also have to take into account that people can live in the</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>community with a mental illness, and they can function very well. We would look at, you know, has this person had contact with the AFP? Has there been presentations to a hospital? So we take a lot of things into account, but people do have the right to live with a mental illness in the community, and not necessarily be harassed by us. But we also are looking at risks to themselves,</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>and the risk to others. So there's many ways that we can do that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  I would individualise the - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  That's what I was saying. We can't say there's a blanket - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHl08/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-16</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: From the tribunal, I hope with support of the other members, would say that in this case if Wendell says he's going to continue treatment, and he doesn't, then you ought to immediately apply for an assessment order.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON: Apply for an assessment order.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  So we can compulsorily get him back into treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: Because he does need to stay in treatment, and he's telling us he's going to.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  Would you need an assessment order, or</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>would you just apply-with all of this information, wouldn't you just apply for a psychiatric treatment order?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DRDREW: YoucouldapplyforaPTO.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON: Psychiatric treatment order, yes. I guess the risk - the only - the real risk that I see in this situation is if you become - it remains itinerant, and doesn't go through with housing, is, you know, also locating somebody with the sort of a history of not engaging.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  I think that is a serious issue.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  I see that as a big issue.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  A psychiatric treatment order doesn't make someone</p><p style="text-align: center;">30Â  contactable, because what I see on a regular basis is applications for revocation which say the person we believe has moved interstate and is no longer a person in relation to whom a psychiatric treatment order can be made.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  We do see that, is what - Dr Drew's point,</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>I think, in saying having a psychiatric treatment order sometimes can provide people with an incentive to move interstate.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  It is possible, but then - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40Â  MS HANSON: We may also, you know, advise - you know, get in contact with mental health services in that state that we think they are, and let them know that they have been on a treatment order in the ACT.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  Look, we don't want to push - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: No, we're not trying to put Mr Nesmith away. We're trying to support him in the best way possible.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  Ultimately I think the best option would be for him to not have a</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>treatment order, but for you to be very aware that we expect you'll apply for either an assessment order, a treatment order ifh doesn't turn up for treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: I think we have additional risks though. The risks are you can't follow up Wendell in the same way that you can follow up other people</p><p style="text-align: center;">IO<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>because you don't know where he lives, and you can't - - - MR NESMITH: I'll show you.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  The staff can't - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MR NESMITH: (indistinct) MS HANSON: It's not realistic.</p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  Wendell, I think all of this was showing that the treatment is</p><p style="text-align: center;">25Â  having an effect. Because you were no way inclined to tell us last time where you were. You said it was so far away no-one would find it. You didn't want anybody to find it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  There is a difference between telling you where it is, and</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>showing you where it is. Because if I'm showing you where it is, you've made a commitment to see a little bit about my life that most people wouldn't even be interested in. So to me that would be meaningful if you - someone from the treating team could go with me, and I could just show them one time where I live, that would be really awesome. I would - I think that would be really kind</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>ofyou.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: You could meet them at a certain - you know, at a fence line.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  I could.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  (indistinct).</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-18</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  (indistinct) activity (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: It's never been Mount Ainslie. I've never said Mount Ainslie.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES:Â  I thought it was Mount Ainslie</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Yes, actually (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BATES:Â  (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  It's all through the reports - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: I think this is the risk. For me, I'm still concerned. I'm concerned because we're relying entirely on Wendell to contact the service, and we have a long history going back to 2010, 2011 where he has dropped out of treatment. You don't have the same tools in your toolkit that</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>you normally have. You can't drop in on him, you can't put a letter under his door, or a card in his letterbox. You've had problems phoning Wendell today.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: No. No problems phoning him. We didn't have the right number.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: But the onus is entirely on Wendell, and that worries me.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  With the PTO, the same things apply. You're not going to find</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>him just because he's on a PTO.</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: But then there's that over-arching-.- - MS HALSEY: We have an avenue of being able to advise the police that we</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>need to locate this person.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Wendell knows he has to come in - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  My concern is why wouldn't - if you had</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>concerns for a voluntary patient's health and wellbeing, wouldn't you also call the police and say, "We have this patient. They're a voluntary patient, but we haven't seen them for three weeks, and now we've got concerns about their wellbeing."</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HALSEY:Â  We do do that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHl 08/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-19</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So you don't need a PTO to call the police?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HALSEY: No, you don't need a PTO to call the police, but they are more inclined to assist us if somebody is - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS HANSON: (indistinct) MS HALSEY: (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  I guess it's because they're resources. Having a welfare check</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>done is - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Everyone has resource problems, and</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>that's part of our concern here.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Can I also just add that on the review that Mr Nesmith had with Dr Flynn the other day was where he did actually say, and I'm happy to provide you with a copy of this, that, you know, "Just let me be a free man.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>Why should you care what I believe in, or what my inclinations are?" So to me that - does that indicate, you know, that he wants to always engage with the team?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  He's talking about his work.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I'm talking about my work. PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Yes, Mr Nesmith?</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MR NESMITH: The only time that I've ever fallen out of treatment was when I moved interstate and then having to do all the reconnections, because when you move interstate and you're homeless, you're moving from one place - you're homeless in one state, and then you move to another state, and you're homeless in that state, you have to find all the resources. The first thing you</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>need is food.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Now, Mr Nesmith, I have to tell you I think that you minimise the extent to which you weren't proactive getting back into treatment, because we've got the notes from 2011, and these are the notes</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>from, I think, Ballarat. You reported having returned to Australia, and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-20</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">accommodation had fallen through. You'd become homeless in Melbourne where you'd been homeless for two and a half week, then walked to Melton, obtaining a lift to Bathurst Marsh. Police put you on the train to Ballarat.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>You had - then you went and (indistinct) living in the bush, and then the guesthouse. So you lived in the bush on the outskirts of Ballarat for three to four weeks. So that was June 2011.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Our notes are in between 2012 and 2013 do indicate, you</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>know, there was a lot of difficulty getting Mr Nesmith to remain engaged with the team whilst he was here in the ACT. There were a number ofreports - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>15</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So he was in the ACT - what dates were that?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: That 2012, 2013. PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So he - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON: There was a number of contacts with the AFP during that time as well.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: On the other hand, now he's got such a committed health team---</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  He'll go hiking up Mount Ainslie.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  Hike up there with your (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DREW:Â  It is five years ago.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: It is, yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  This time Wendell has been in treatment for about, what, six</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>weeks? Four lo six weeks? He's changed - - - MS HANSON: It wonldn't even be that long.</p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  Well, he's changed dramatically since when we saw him last</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>time.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: (indistinct) oral medication prior to going to (indistinct) is what I understand.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DREW:Â  So I think he's shown significant change and improvement as a</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">result of treatment. I think you ought to keep on the treatment. MR NESMITH: I will, sir. Thank you, Dr Drew.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>DR DREW: With a community health - mental health team. I don't care where he lives. Ifhe likes - I'd like to live up there with him, but I don't need to. I've got birds all around me evidently. I'm just lucky. But you know - but he's also talking about coming back and living in town.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HALSEY: Absolutely. We're in close contact all the time. So I'm an extra level of support.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Chris has really helped.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DREW:Â  I think we all want to work as cooperatively as possible. Sorry.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  That's okay. I don't take it personally.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  We're just really representing the psychiatrists.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: I guess - I sort of - ifI can ask a question about - you've been in the sort of emergency, crisis accommodation in the past, and that hasn't worked.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH: It's dangerous. Like, in the Ballarat case, someone actually broke into my window while I was sleeping. So I caught someone in the middle of climbing into my window. I'm like, "What? What are you doing."</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Have you been in emergency or</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>supportive accommodation in the ACT in the past?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I don't want to because - for example, this morning I went to Havelock House, and then I asked the administration if it was safe. First she went like. Then she went.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  You're kidding?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Then she went. I'm much better in the mountain than I am in a position where - I'm a very sensitive person. I don't want people arguing. I</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>mean, not just arguing. They yell. They smash things, and they scream. I don't want that in my life at all.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  Yes. So - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  I would be much happier in the mountain than in that</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">position. That's why I need to work with housing to - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  But you're pursuing the option of getting your own housing.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  Yes. That's what I (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: But the likelihood of that happening in a short period of time - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BATES: What Wendell wants - it's not so much that he's against emergency accommodation. What he wants is accommodation where wherever he is, it's self-contained. Like, he has his own bathroom, and he has</p><p style="text-align: center;">his own cooking facilities. Where he has to share bathrooms and share cooking facilities, he's not keen on that, because then you have this level of - you know?</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I need a man cave. MS BATES:Â  He needs a man cave.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Because I saw on our notes that perhaps you'd been at Samaritan House in the past, and that hadn't worked out before.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  Have you been in Samaritan House?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  I don't remember. I don't think so.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  I'm not aware of that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  I don't think so. Like, I learned in Ballarat how dangerous</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>crisis accommodation is. Ever since Ballarat I've done everything that I could to stay away from it, because I know how it is.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  Which is why he lives how he lives.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PRESIDENTMEMBERDANIEL: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DAVEY: Each time he moves, he falls out of treatment, and he is socially isolated and we go back to square one. What I'm seeing here is history of him in and out of treatment, and not being adequately treated.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  If you help me, I'll stay here.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DAVEY: Wendell, that's what I'm proposing to help you. I'm seeing that you're an intelligent, capable person who could be so much better on treatment,</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>who needs to stay in treatment, and who needs to be in regular contact with</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">people in order to stay well. What we have here is an under-treated history where you have been itinerant, and you have fallen out of treatment. I actually think you should be on an order, because I want to see you being happy and healthy for a while.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">I don't care whether you live in a tent either. I don't think it's the best place for you to live. I think you're too young and capable to be socially isolated, but you need to be where people can look after you, where you can make friends. What about your issues about finding a wife? You've been talking about</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>finding a wife.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I'm still doing it, but I want to do it through the Internet. I think that's actually really good, because paving a new way for people to meet each other. By my putting my heart out on the Internet for the entire world to</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>see, eventually I'll get led to that person that - like, I'm famous. In the US I'm really popular. The thing is that will eventually lead to someone who wants what I have to offer. So I think in the future it's going to happen a lot more often because you can match really, really good people together if you just use the Internet to see yourself.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  That's not a new concept.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: It's not a dating site. It's not a dating site. It's standing in front of a camera, holding the camera pointing back at you, and talking to that</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>camera about your life and how you feel about everything, and what is meaningful to you, and what you hate about the world, and what you love about the world. That's how I want to meet my wife. I'm willing to wait. That's okay. I'm a very patient person. In philosophy we've got - we learn patients very well.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES:Â  May I address the tribunal?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  Yes. We're just exploring things.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS BATES: Yes, I can see. I think the discussion has been incredibly helpful (indistinct) Member Davey, I can see your concerns, and it's your concerns I'd like to address primarily. It's coming down to what kind of treatment would he get on a PTO versus what kind of treatment would he get (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DAVEY:Â  That's not what concerns me.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES:Â  Oh.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DAVEY:Â  I don't think he's going to accept treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHl08/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-24</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES:Â  I'll come back to your concerns.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Deal with Dr Davey's concerns, then come back to mine.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES: Arguably there really isn't a (indistinct) in this case. Your concern is about the long term and whether or not he'll continue to engage, and in particular the treatment team being able to engage with him. Being able to (indistinct) if something goes wrong. I can't see how a PTO being in place</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>would change any of that, and so arguably it's not the least restrictive option in this case.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">The least restrictive option is there not being a psychiatric treatment order, and to engage voluntarily. I do recognise your concerns, but I think in some</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>situations it might be the case that PTO would provide something that not being on a PTO wouldn't provide. I can't see how that's the case in this situation.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DAVEY:Â  I can. I can see that Wendell knows that he has to attend for</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>treatment, and the onus is on him, and to come down from the mountain to attend, as opposed to people finding him in an undisclosed location. I think the other option there is with a PTO, ifhe does - ifwe do lose him, then we can at least call the police as well. So I think my concern is that this is very oneÂ­ sided. It's putting the treating team in a very difficult position, and I want</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Wendell to have some sort of obligation to come down the mountain.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  He does that every day, Dr Davey.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DAVEY:Â  Into treatment. He does while he is under this.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY: No, he does it every day. He has to. To get water, to get gas for his heater. He comes every day. I've been in touch with him every day, and he has the same routine every day.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DAVEY: (indistinct) I think that's right for food, and for social contact, but in order to receive treatment, he's very clever. He's done this for the last seven or eight, or more years. He knows that until we've made this decision</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>that he has to toe the line. The history tells me that he hasn't toed the line once he's gone off the treatment order. That's my concern. I want him to be well, and I want him to function adequately, and healthily and happily. Up until now he hasn't. That's what you have to convince me about.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BATES:Â  While he has had this process hanging over his head arguably,</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-25</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">like Dr Drew mentioned earlier (indistinct) he hasn't been under any kind of order since he was released (indistinct) he has expressed, not only verbally but through his actions, a willingness to engage. He has come down - he's been given depot injections which are - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: One in hospital, and one since discharge.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES: Which are invasive. Let's not (indistinct) you know, nobody else has to go through that. He has expressed his willingness to.do that, and to</p><p style="text-align: center;">IO<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>continue to do that. I note you're looking at the history, and that - look, I can't argue against that. There is history that's problematic, but on this occasion, and this is what we need to be primarily looking at, I understand that you need to also look at the history to determine whether or not somebody is going (indistinct) but primarily in this case he has shown a willingness, and expressed</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>a willingness to consent to continue this treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">I think it would be a far more therapeutic process for him to be engaged voluntarily on this occasion. It's also - I mean, the tribunal has said this before, "This is your last chance," you know? This is - like, "We've given you chances</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>before. You can't just keep doing this. Eventually you're going to be on a psychiatric treatment order." I think given the history - the length oftime he's been engaged with - I think the previous presentation in the ACT was 2013. Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>I think given that time in between, noting that there has been extreme (indistinct) I think it's worthwhile giving him another chance. From a legal point of view I really - I would argue the (indistinct) can be fully demonstrated in this case. I think - which is the key question here. But also I think there is a less restrictive option available, and I think (indistinct) in this case.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">DRDAVEY: Ifitworks. MS BATES: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DAVEY:Â  There's a I 0-year history of it not working.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  Can I ask a question?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  We might adjourn and discuss it unless</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>anyone wants to make any further comments.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: Can I say one other thing? Can I suggest that very quickly someone from the treatment team goes with Wendell up to see where he does live, and then when you call the police you'll know where to send them.</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHI0S/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-26</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: That's a good idea. MS HALSEY: I put my hand up for that.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: On a sunny day. Not a rainy day. Does anyone have any other submissions they'd like to make before we adjourn to consider - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  I just wanted to ask a question because I - I'm not - I didn't read</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>all of the notes, but when he was under a treatment order in Queensland - - - PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: On what occasion?</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  I believe it was 2016.</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: 2016, yes. MS MABEY: Yes. Did he - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">20Â  PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: It was revoked on 16 June, because he said he'd take treatment. He was discharged on Olanzapine on 7 July 2016, and that's where the records stop.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  Did you continue treatment after the treatment order?</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I did, yes. I actually already told you about this. When I went to the US, and it was $600 per month. I cannot afford that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  Then he came back to - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  How long did you go to the states for?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I was there for six months, then I went to Mexico for one year, and then I came from Mexico to here.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: To Canberra.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DAVEY:Â  Which is when you presented to City Mental Health.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  I've been here for four months almost.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY: And there's been concerns about his mental state for that time. PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Okay. Ms Bates, do you want to say</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>something before we're adjourned?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-27 .</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES: In regards to police, even if - if somebody is on a PTO I understand having that piece of paper is helpful, but you can (indistinct) issues. We believe there is a risk, and - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Well, there has already been contact with the AFP, obviously, because that's how he was taken to the hospital, because of concerns with his behaviour at Centrelink.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS BATES: So while we can never predict how the police will react in any given situation, noting that there has been (indistinct) incident, they would arguably take this one seriously, regardless of whether a PTO is in place. I think that the police would take it seriously. Thank you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Ms Halsey, I think we understand your position that we shouldn't make an order.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ADJOURNED</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>RESUMED</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(4.23 pm]</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">[4.31 pm]</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So we're resuming matter MH108 of 2012.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DREW: Can I say I'm going to excuse myself. I have another appointment I have to go to, but I've made my position plain to everybody before.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Thank you, Dr Drew.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Look, obviously this is a very difficult decision, and in fact the tribunal is not in agreement about it. Dr Drew has made his view clear, and - that he does not think that it's appropriate to make the psychiatric treatment order, and certainly the most therapeutic situation</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>would be voluntary treatment. I can say the tribunal is in agreement in these respects. We do think that Mr Nesmith has a mental illness.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">We do think that without treatment he is likely to do harm to himself - serious harm as a result of misadventure or self-neglect, and potentially how people</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>may react to him that leads him to risk, and that also, without treatment, his mental state and functioning will seriously deteriorate. So we're satisfied of those things. What the areas of disagreement focus on are the question of whether Mr Nesmith refuses treatment or not. I know we've had a lot of conversation about what practical effect a PTO would have. In my view, that's</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>not particularly relevant. Legally it might be relevant in practical terms, but it's</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHI 08/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-28</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">not part of the legal test. The legal test is actually does he have a mental illness; what's the risk if not treated; and then this key question, is he refusing treatment?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>Both Dr Davies and I are of the view that there should be a treatment order for six months and the reason why is because, when we look at those medical records, we see a history of a person who continually says to the authorities that he will accept treatment and then it all goes wrong and he's not involved in treatment any more. So just for the purposes of remembering that the best</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>predictor of future behaviour is past behaviour, the records that we have say that he came self-presented to a hospital in June 2011, and this was in Ballarat, with suicidal ideation. At that stage he had not eaten for six days. He was quite unwell and he was admitted to hospital.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>The latest record from that 2011 episode was 31 August 2011 when it wrote that two weeks post-discharge he was to move to Western Australia, he was referred to the WA Mental Health Service, Swan Mental Health. He was going to be living with a supportive bunch of friends and everything was going to be wonderful, but it didn't work out that way. There was no order made because it</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>was all going to be voluntary. It didn't work out because we see that in April 2012 actually he's admitted to the ACT Adult Mental Health Unit, then he's discharged, again voluntary, lost to that service.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">The next thing that happens is he has another admission in Canberra in 2013</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>where he came in, as we discussed previously, through the Emergency Department. Again, an opportunity for him to engage voluntarily in treatment, for what we're satisfied is his mental illness, lost to follow-up treatment. Then he ends up in Lismore in 2014. We don't have the records for that but we do have a reference that he says that he spent a week in prison in Grafton. I don't</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>know whether that's a reference to being kept in hospital or actually a criminal thing, we don't know. But whatever we know is he didn't stay in treatment after coming in to treatment in Lismore; he was out of it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">By 12 April 2016 he is in Queensland. He gets admitted after what sounds like</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>a very risky episode at a caravan park where he's making comments about young women and that could have led him to being misunderstood and physically threatened. Certainly he was brought in under an emergency order to the hospital. He was put on an involuntary treatment order. That was revoked on 16 June. He was discharged on Olanzapine on 7 July 2016 but</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>that's where the records end because he's been lost to treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">We are satisfied on the basis of that record that no matter what Mr Nesmith says and how persuasive he is and genuine - Mr Nesmith, I think you're genuine, and so does Dr Davies, when you tell us you're going to engage in</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>treatment. It's not that we think you're lying to us, we think you're absolutely</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHl 08/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-29</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">honest and genuine, but life interferes with that. But we're confident that with a psychiatric treatment order, because you are a good person and a</p><p style="text-align: center;">rule-conscious person you will comply with that and you won't be lost to treatment while that order is in place.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">So we're going to make an order for six months and we'll review that before it expires and we look forward to hearing what your accommodation turns out being like when we review this. It might be that you're still living where you're living now because you might choose to do that, and that's fine, or you might</p><p style="text-align: center;">IO<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>choose to go into other accommodation. That's fine too. But what's really important is we're ordering that you will continue with the recommended medical treatment for another six months and we'll hear how that's going at the end of those six months. Okay?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  Thank you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Thank you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MATTER ADJOURNED AT 4.38 PM ACCORDINGLY</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /><