enter;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Page 9 of 14</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Illness or mental disorder?<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>IBJYes ? No</p><p style="text-align: center;">Is the person suffering, or likely to suffer serious mental or physical deterioration because of the mental Illness or mental disorder?<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>IBJYes<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Â· ? No</p><p style="text-align: center;">Jfyes, explain your reasons for this opinion.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Risk prediction is a fraught area as clinicians cannot be precise or quantltate risk given the variables and unpredictable nature of people's behaviour and their environments.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">However, the risks to Mr Nesmith Include that the longer he Is left with an untreated psychotic Illness the worse his prognosis and quality of recovery, that could have devastating Impacts on his ability to work, have relationships, Jive and function In society. There Is a potential risk of him falsely Identifying a community member as the "grandmaster" of the Freemasons based on a delusion, and conflict arising with possible violent sequelae although there Is no past history of violent altercations yet that we know of. His lntlnerant and secretlv lifestyle limits any corroborative history. He may be at risk of angering others with his "investigations" and misadventure. There are risks around camping In the bush regions If he was to have physical health issues or not have enough gear for w rmth. Personal safety and security Is also problematic.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Is is not known if Mr Nesmith would self-harm If he became overwhelmed by his predicament and fate of the world. There was the past lncldeht of Inserting a wire Into his penis which may have been due</p><p style="text-align: