egistrar)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Page 10 of 14</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Community follow-up would Include regular contact with a case-manager and doctor, psychological therapy If desired, and assistance linking to services for housing and other goals he may have In his recovery eg further study or work.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">9, Why or how will treatment care or support be likely to reduce harm, or deterioration, or result in an Improvement to the person's condltloni'</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">It Is hoped thut Mr Nesmlth's delusional preoccupations are reversible, and that with treatment he would be able to not be so consumed In saving the world, collect evidence, confronting organisations etc and transfer his Intellect and creativity to other pursuits that hopefully provide Joy, fulfillment and. security and not place him at risk. The risks associated with chronic mental Illness would hopefully be reduced and his quality of life Improved. There Is a possibility that he Is estranged from his US family</p><p style="text-align: center;">due to delusional beliefs and this could potentially be healed and Increase his supports.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10, WhY. can't the treatment care or support f5e