ell spoken and intelligent man, older than stated age. Extremely thin, with a few tattoos on his body. Client speaks with a slight American accent, speech slightly rapid, conversations difficult to interrupt at times. Using good eye contact/ appropriate body language. Wendell was discussing his past, states he was previously married in Western Australia but when he and his wife divorced he became isolated from majority of his friends.; and he is estranged from his family back in America. Began travelling around Australia following this, spent long periods in Victoria, and has come to Canberra as he enjoys studying philosophy - he believes ANU has the best philosophy course in Australia.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Regarding his selective mutism - he says the treating team have never asked why he is reluctant to communicate with his voice, that he has the right to remain silent, and that he should have the right to a pen and paper. Feels actions like confiscating his kindle (electronic reader) because he "won't conform to our institutions expectations" are punitive,</p><p style="text-align: center;">Denies auditory hallucinations /visual hallucinations; nil evidence of responding to internal stimuli. Clearly has some quite eccentric beliefs, but not observed to have any evidence of formal thought disorder. Wendell has been calm and polite during all conversations, both with myself and other clients. Later in the shift he sat with myself, another nurse and several HOU consumers and taught all ofus some Origami. Extremely calm, gentle and polite entire time, showing a lot of patience with others.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Reports his mood as "great, very happy". Mood has affect have been stable throughout duration of shift, interacting well with consumer and majority of staff.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Client is adamant he would like a new doctor; reports this as his biggest need. States his current treating team have not been willing to spend any time with him unless he communicates verbally and would like to speak to speak with a doctor that shows more interest in him.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><span style="white-space: normal;"><span style="white-space: pre;">	</span> p.,jnfArl nn â€¢</span></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Â· 111111111111 IIIII Ill111111111111111</p><p style="text-align: center;">*40260*</p><p style="text-align: center;">The Canberra Hospital</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Patient Progress</p><p style="text-align: center;">From<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>28/04/2012 ToÂ  07/05/2012</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">UR Number 20163678 Surname<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span> Nesmith First Name<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span> Wendell Ct DOB<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>27/06/1984</p><p style="text-align: center;">Address<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Unknown</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Unknown</p><p style="text-align: center;">9999<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>UNK</p><p style="text-align: center;">Home Phone Unknown</p><p style="text-align: center;">Work Phone</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Page No.<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>25</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Gender<span style