he cannot weigh up the consequences of thEJ main choices; he cannot understand how the consequences affect him; and he cannot make the decision on the basis of the</p><p style="text-align: center;">matters set out above.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(iv) Wendell Charles Nesmith refuses the treatment determined in relation to himself because although he says he will accept treatment and in the very recent past has been accepting treatment; he has a 7 year history of ceasing treatment afterÂ· advising health authorities he will continue with treatment. The Tribunal considers his current compliance with treatment is of a short duration and against the extensive history is of the view that he refuses treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(v) The Tribunal believes on reasonable grounds that because of his mental illness, Wendell Charles Nesmith is likely to do serious harm to himself as a result of misadventure or self neglect when unwell.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(vi) The Tribunal believes on reasonable grounds that because of his mental illness, Wendell Charles Nesmith is likely to suffer serious deterioration of his mental state and functioning if untreated,</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(vii)Â </p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">I)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">The Tribunal is satisfied that psychiatric treatment, care or support is likely to reciuce the likelihood of harm or deterioration mentioned above and is likely to result in an improvement in Wendell Charles Nesmith's psychiatric condition.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br />