r;">SENIOR MEMBER DREW: I think you should. It will make your life so much better.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MRNESMITH: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">SENIOR MEMBER DREW: It really will because otherwise you will be tortured all the time because people will just continue taking you back to hospital.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: You don't want that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: When I refer to torture I'm talking, I'm referring to the hospital specifically. I'm not talking about anything outside of the hospital, sir.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5Â  SENIOR MEMBER DREW: No, no. It's also if you don't take, if you do have treatment continuing you will be much more productive than you are. Really productive.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I agree. I agree.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So I guess we now understand that the proposed treatment plan is going forward, and we understand the concerns that Dr Flynn has, that - and we've got - read through the notes that we can read.</p><p style="text-align: center;">We understand that there's a history of falling out of treatment, and some of</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>that is because of the medication being too expensive while he was overseas, some of it is around - it was actually - there was times where the medication prescribed to you did not work for you as well.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">So for whatever reason there's been a failure to get adequate treatment, or</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>engage with adequate treatment in the past. I might just ask Ms BATES first. Ms BATES, do you have any questions for Ms Hanson about the proposed treatment, engagement with treatment, acceptance of treatment, anything on this topic?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS BATES: Thank you. Despite the reasoning for engagement in treatment, has Wendell been engaging since he was released (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  So he did come to the review, yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BATES: He has presented (indistinct) MS HANSON: Yes, he did.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES: Just to clarify- - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: I think that did take quite a number of - like, we did actually have to spend some time locating him. His phone was not working, was not accepting incoming calls.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  You had the wrong number.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  I came in - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-11</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Yes, when we contacted</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  It was apparently, like, an hour after you called.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BATES:Â  Is the plan to move to (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Well, that will be dependent on whether this - you know, medication does work for him. This is a fortnightly medication. However, on a higher dose it can be changed to a monthly injection, yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES:Â  This is a better print.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  I don't need a copy.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DREW:Â  You don't need a copy?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  No.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES:Â  This is (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Yes. This is a better print-out, Ms l;lATES, than the one I gave you. It's much more readable.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  It couldn't be worse.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: It couldn't. Ms Halsey, did you have any questions for Ms Hanson on the topic of treatment plans, and treatment engagement?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HALSEY: As you're probably aware I've been keeping in fairly close contact with Wendell, and meeting up with him, and involved in the housing applications and that sort of thing. Now, I understand that he was allocated a case manager, Nakem. But Nakem is on leave currently, so Ke! has taken over. Ke! is who Wendell thought was his case manager, but I understand that Ke! is</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>the duty manager that's just been - - - MS HANSON: Yes, standing in. Yeah.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  But the last - I know that the last few days Ke! hasn't been at</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>work either.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  No, Ke! hasn't been there either.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  So there hasn't actually been a case manager for Wendell to</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>connect with, but he has tried. I mean, he's been taking paperwork in that sort</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MFII0S/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-12</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ofthing.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Yes. We did receive his housing application yesterday. It</p><p style="text-align: center;">was yesterday, wasn't it, that you dropped it in? We've got a support officer</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>that will be actually also working with Mr Nesmith to get that lodged.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  And the DSP, that sort of thing?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Yes. I think Dr Flynn is going to do a supporting letter in</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>relation to the housing.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY: Good. I'm happy to do a supporting letter for the housing as well. But I thought that when I was talking to Kate - when I was talking to you the other day, Kate, that the housing application had already been done, and it</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>just needed - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: It had been given.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  - - - the bank statements, and the 100 points.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Yes, we I think we were waiting from my instructors on the 100 points ID which now we have. So it's just a matter I think of - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  Going into housing.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Yes. I think as (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: That was all into social housing. We still have the regular housing to do, which she's - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  For ACT Housing.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Chris can help me with that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HALSEY: So you know, he has been making - he's been coming into City Mental Health, he's been engaging, he's done his psychiatric review, he's coming for his depot. Quite happy to have the depot, and engage in care treatment and support, and I think that he is really quite committed to staying in Canberra at this stage. He wants ACT Housing.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">He wants secure housing so that he can come down and stop living in his tent. So I think that shows a commitment that he is not going to abscond. He's not going to be itinerant any more. He actually wants to stay here, and he wants to actually do his work here. So I don't think there's - from my point of view I</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>don't think there's any (indistinct) at this stage. I don't think there's a case to be</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">made for refusing it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: Can I just ask- I don't want to be rude in saying this, but is the city mental the best (indistinct) to be involving Wendell?</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Yes, I think we are. Yes. I think we've got - - - MR NESMITH: They're really good.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DREW:Â  I know they're very good but they're also very stretched.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Yes. I think we're working very hard to try and support him. You know, we don't really have a choice at this particular point in time because he is living within our catchment area anyway. You know, that could change.</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  I was thinking about supported accommodation.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Well, the fact that Mr Nesmith is engaging in treatment, so he wouldn't actually meet their criteria. But if that changed, well, then there is</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>that possibility, and that's irrespective of where he lives in Canberra.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  (indistinct) is that going to make any difference?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  I think the concern - my understanding from Dr Flynn is this</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>sort of history of non-engagement or being itinerant, and not actually continuing with treatment on a sort of a long enough basis.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  Sorry, I was looking at it from the opposite end.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON:Â  Okay.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: If you want a PTO, you find a - you're obliged to look after it. If</p><p style="text-align: center;">he's not on a PTO, well, he might fall off.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON: Well, that's what my understanding is. That's what's happened in the past back in 2012 when he was sort of lost to (indistinct) the ACT.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  Yes, but that might have been his. fault. I'm concerned it might</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>be your fault.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Well - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  Would you disengage ifhe wasn't on a</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PTO?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHl 08/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-14</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Would we disengage? No. No, we would not.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  I mean, I've he's on a PTO, you've got to actively go out and see</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>him every two weeks.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Yes, we do, but I - you know - well, I believe that we do actively also, you know, support a lot of people who aren't on PTOs. We are very stretched, but - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: I'm not concerned - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Can you tell me - I'm going to ask a procedural - this is an office question. You have a number of open files. Some</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>of them are on people who are voluntary patients. A patient stops coming to see you. When do you close the file?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: There are so many different circumstances or, you know, situations to take into account. If a person is refusing to engage with us then</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>that's completely different. I mean, we will do everything we possibly can based on assessments. We may even look at having to get an assessment order to actually get that person to re-engage. We don't just - we try not to just stop. There's loads of people we don't do that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS MABEY:Â  We try not to do that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  I'm just wondering because - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  We have an MDT process.</p><p style="text-align: center;">(<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>30</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  Well, I want to know what the process is.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: So if somebody was having difficulty engaging with a client, or getting a client to engage with us, we would ask - we would - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: A voluntary client.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: A voluntary client, yes. We would - first of all you might seek some peer support. You might discuss it with the doctor that last</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>reviewed that person. You would take it to an MDT process where - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Joe failed to turn up at his review this week, and I rang and left a message, and he's never called me back?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON:Â  Yes. So we will start, you know, looking at do we go and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHI0S/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-15</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">knock on that person's door? Do we start contacting family? Next of kin? As I said, we will discuss it in a multi-disciplinary team meeting as to how we can engage that person. You know, maybe there's somebody else on the team that has worked with that person in the past, and they might, you know, have some</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>ideas. You know, just continually inviting them in. We don't just - we tend to not just let people just drop off the books.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Then what happens? So you've tried for a month, and the phone calls haven't been replied to, and you've been up to the</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>house, and they've - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: Can I just say in this case. In other cases you might just let it drop.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS HANSON: You do also sometimes have to respect a person's right to - if they're voluntary, to choose to engage with - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  That's what I'm interested in.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON:Â  We do have to respect that, and we do.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So you have a patient with mental health because you think they've got a mental illness which is being treated by medication and monitoring. They cease taking the medication, they cease</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>engaging in monitoring, and yet sometimes it seems to me files just get closed, whereas I would have thought that all of that background information, if you know someone has a mental illness which leave them at risk of misadventure, or neglect, or whatever, and they cease engaging with their treatment and with their monitoring, wouldn't that mean you should apply for an assessment</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>order?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Every case is an individual, and I can't answer that question based on everybody who ceases engagement with the city mental health team. You know, I think we also have to take into account that people can live in the</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>community with a mental illness, and they can function very well. We would look at, you know, has this person had contact with the AFP? Has there been presentations to a hospital? So we take a lot of things into account, but people do have the right to live with a mental illness in the community, and not necessarily be harassed by us. But we also are looking at risks to themselves,</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>and the risk to others. So there's many ways that we can do that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  I would individualise the - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  That's what I was saying. We can't say there's a blanket - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHl08/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-16</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: From the tribunal, I hope with support of the other members, would say that in this case if Wendell says he's going to continue treatment, and he doesn't, then you ought to immediately apply for an assessment order.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON: Apply for an assessment order.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  So we can compulsorily get him back into treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10</p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: Because he does need to stay in treatment, and he's telling us he's going to.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  Would you need an assessment order, or</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>would you just apply-with all of this information, wouldn't you just apply for a psychiatric treatment order?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DRDREW: YoucouldapplyforaPTO.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON: Psychiatric treatment order, yes. I guess the risk - the only - the real risk that I see in this situation is if you become - it remains itinerant, and doesn't go through with housing, is, you know, also locating somebody with the sort of a history of not engaging.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  I think that is a serious issue.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  I see that as a big issue.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  A psychiatric treatment order doesn't make someone</p><p style="text-align: center;">30Â  contactable, because what I see on a regular basis is applications for revocation which say the person we believe has moved interstate and is no longer a person in relation to whom a psychiatric treatment order can be made.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  We do see that, is what - Dr Drew's point,</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>I think, in saying having a psychiatric treatment order sometimes can provide people with an incentive to move interstate.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  It is possible, but then - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40Â  MS HANSON: We may also, you know, advise - you know, get in contact with mental health services in that state that we think they are, and let them know that they have been on a treatment order in the ACT.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  Look, we don't want to push - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: No, we're not trying to put Mr Nesmith away. We're trying to support him in the best way possible.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  Ultimately I think the best option would be for him to not have a</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>treatment order, but for you to be very aware that we expect you'll apply for either an assessment order, a treatment order ifh doesn't turn up for treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: I think we have additional risks though. The risks are you can't follow up Wendell in the same way that you can follow up other people</p><p style="text-align: center;">IO<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>because you don't know where he lives, and you can't - - - MR NESMITH: I'll show you.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  The staff can't - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MR NESMITH: (indistinct) MS HANSON: It's not realistic.</p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  Wendell, I think all of this was showing that the treatment is</p><p style="text-align: center;">25Â  having an effect. Because you were no way inclined to tell us last time where you were. You said it was so far away no-one would find it. You didn't want anybody to find it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  There is a difference between telling you where it is, and</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>showing you where it is. Because if I'm showing you where it is, you've made a commitment to see a little bit about my life that most people wouldn't even be interested in. So to me that would be meaningful if you - someone from the treating team could go with me, and I could just show them one time where I live, that would be really awesome. I would - I think that would be really kind</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>ofyou.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: You could meet them at a certain - you know, at a fence line.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  I could.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  (indistinct).</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-18</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  (indistinct) activity (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: It's never been Mount Ainslie. I've never said Mount Ainslie.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES:Â  I thought it was Mount Ainslie</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Yes, actually (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BATES:Â  (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  It's all through the reports - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: I think this is the risk. For me, I'm still concerned. I'm concerned because we're relying entirely on Wendell to contact the service, and we have a long history going back to 2010, 2011 where he has dropped out of treatment. You don't have the same tools in your toolkit that</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>you normally have. You can't drop in on him, you can't put a letter under his door, or a card in his letterbox. You've had problems phoning Wendell today.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: No. No problems phoning him. We didn't have the right number.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: But the onus is entirely on Wendell, and that worries me.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  With the PTO, the same things apply. You're not going to find</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>him just because he's on a PTO.</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: But then there's that over-arching-.- - MS HALSEY: We have an avenue of being able to advise the police that we</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>need to locate this person.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Wendell knows he has to come in - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  My concern is why wouldn't - if you had</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>concerns for a voluntary patient's health and wellbeing, wouldn't you also call the police and say, "We have this patient. They're a voluntary patient, but we haven't seen them for three weeks, and now we've got concerns about their wellbeing."</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HALSEY:Â  We do do that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHl 08/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-19</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So you don't need a PTO to call the police?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HALSEY: No, you don't need a PTO to call the police, but they are more inclined to assist us if somebody is - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS HANSON: (indistinct) MS HALSEY: (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  I guess it's because they're resources. Having a welfare check</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>done is - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Everyone has resource problems, and</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>that's part of our concern here.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: Can I also just add that on the review that Mr Nesmith had with Dr Flynn the other day was where he did actually say, and I'm happy to provide you with a copy of this, that, you know, "Just let me be a free man.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>Why should you care what I believe in, or what my inclinations are?" So to me that - does that indicate, you know, that he wants to always engage with the team?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  He's talking about his work.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I'm talking about my work. PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Yes, Mr Nesmith?</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MR NESMITH: The only time that I've ever fallen out of treatment was when I moved interstate and then having to do all the reconnections, because when you move interstate and you're homeless, you're moving from one place - you're homeless in one state, and then you move to another state, and you're homeless in that state, you have to find all the resources. The first thing you</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>need is food.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Now, Mr Nesmith, I have to tell you I think that you minimise the extent to which you weren't proactive getting back into treatment, because we've got the notes from 2011, and these are the notes</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>from, I think, Ballarat. You reported having returned to Australia, and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-20</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">accommodation had fallen through. You'd become homeless in Melbourne where you'd been homeless for two and a half week, then walked to Melton, obtaining a lift to Bathurst Marsh. Police put you on the train to Ballarat.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>You had - then you went and (indistinct) living in the bush, and then the guesthouse. So you lived in the bush on the outskirts of Ballarat for three to four weeks. So that was June 2011.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  Our notes are in between 2012 and 2013 do indicate, you</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>know, there was a lot of difficulty getting Mr Nesmith to remain engaged with the team whilst he was here in the ACT. There were a number ofreports - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>15</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So he was in the ACT - what dates were that?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: That 2012, 2013. PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So he - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HANSON: There was a number of contacts with the AFP during that time as well.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: On the other hand, now he's got such a committed health team---</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  He'll go hiking up Mount Ainslie.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  Hike up there with your (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DREW:Â  It is five years ago.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: It is, yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  This time Wendell has been in treatment for about, what, six</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>weeks? Four lo six weeks? He's changed - - - MS HANSON: It wonldn't even be that long.</p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  Well, he's changed dramatically since when we saw him last</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>time.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON: (indistinct) oral medication prior to going to (indistinct) is what I understand.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DREW:Â  So I think he's shown significant change and improvement as a</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">result of treatment. I think you ought to keep on the treatment. MR NESMITH: I will, sir. Thank you, Dr Drew.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>DR DREW: With a community health - mental health team. I don't care where he lives. Ifhe likes - I'd like to live up there with him, but I don't need to. I've got birds all around me evidently. I'm just lucky. But you know - but he's also talking about coming back and living in town.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS HALSEY: Absolutely. We're in close contact all the time. So I'm an extra level of support.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Chris has really helped.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DREW:Â  I think we all want to work as cooperatively as possible. Sorry.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HALSEY:Â  That's okay. I don't take it personally.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS HANSON:Â  We're just really representing the psychiatrists.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: I guess - I sort of - ifI can ask a question about - you've been in the sort of emergency, crisis accommodation in the past, and that hasn't worked.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH: It's dangerous. Like, in the Ballarat case, someone actually broke into my window while I was sleeping. So I caught someone in the middle of climbing into my window. I'm like, "What? What are you doing."</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Have you been in emergency or</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>supportive accommodation in the ACT in the past?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I don't want to because - for example, this morning I went to Havelock House, and then I asked the administration if it was safe. First she went like. Then she went.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  You're kidding?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: Then she went. I'm much better in the mountain than I am in a position where - I'm a very sensitive person. I don't want people arguing. I</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>mean, not just arguing. They yell. They smash things, and they scream. I don't want that in my life at all.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  Yes. So - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  I would be much happier in the mountain than in that</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">position. That's why I need to work with housing to - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW:Â  But you're pursuing the option of getting your own housing.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  Yes. That's what I (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: But the likelihood of that happening in a short period of time - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BATES: What Wendell wants - it's not so much that he's against emergency accommodation. What he wants is accommodation where wherever he is, it's self-contained. Like, he has his own bathroom, and he has</p><p style="text-align: center;">his own cooking facilities. Where he has to share bathrooms and share cooking facilities, he's not keen on that, because then you have this level of - you know?</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I need a man cave. MS BATES:Â  He needs a man cave.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Because I saw on our notes that perhaps you'd been at Samaritan House in the past, and that hadn't worked out before.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  Have you been in Samaritan House?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  I don't remember. I don't think so.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  I'm not aware of that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  I don't think so. Like, I learned in Ballarat how dangerous</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>crisis accommodation is. Ever since Ballarat I've done everything that I could to stay away from it, because I know how it is.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  Which is why he lives how he lives.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PRESIDENTMEMBERDANIEL: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DAVEY: Each time he moves, he falls out of treatment, and he is socially isolated and we go back to square one. What I'm seeing here is history of him in and out of treatment, and not being adequately treated.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  If you help me, I'll stay here.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DAVEY: Wendell, that's what I'm proposing to help you. I'm seeing that you're an intelligent, capable person who could be so much better on treatment,</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>who needs to stay in treatment, and who needs to be in regular contact with</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">people in order to stay well. What we have here is an under-treated history where you have been itinerant, and you have fallen out of treatment. I actually think you should be on an order, because I want to see you being happy and healthy for a while.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">I don't care whether you live in a tent either. I don't think it's the best place for you to live. I think you're too young and capable to be socially isolated, but you need to be where people can look after you, where you can make friends. What about your issues about finding a wife? You've been talking about</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>finding a wife.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I'm still doing it, but I want to do it through the Internet. I think that's actually really good, because paving a new way for people to meet each other. By my putting my heart out on the Internet for the entire world to</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>see, eventually I'll get led to that person that - like, I'm famous. In the US I'm really popular. The thing is that will eventually lead to someone who wants what I have to offer. So I think in the future it's going to happen a lot more often because you can match really, really good people together if you just use the Internet to see yourself.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  That's not a new concept.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: It's not a dating site. It's not a dating site. It's standing in front of a camera, holding the camera pointing back at you, and talking to that</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>camera about your life and how you feel about everything, and what is meaningful to you, and what you hate about the world, and what you love about the world. That's how I want to meet my wife. I'm willing to wait. That's okay. I'm a very patient person. In philosophy we've got - we learn patients very well.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES:Â  May I address the tribunal?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  Yes. We're just exploring things.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS BATES: Yes, I can see. I think the discussion has been incredibly helpful (indistinct) Member Davey, I can see your concerns, and it's your concerns I'd like to address primarily. It's coming down to what kind of treatment would he get on a PTO versus what kind of treatment would he get (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DAVEY:Â  That's not what concerns me.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES:Â  Oh.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DAVEY:Â  I don't think he's going to accept treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHl08/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-24</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES:Â  I'll come back to your concerns.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Deal with Dr Davey's concerns, then come back to mine.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES: Arguably there really isn't a (indistinct) in this case. Your concern is about the long term and whether or not he'll continue to engage, and in particular the treatment team being able to engage with him. Being able to (indistinct) if something goes wrong. I can't see how a PTO being in place</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>would change any of that, and so arguably it's not the least restrictive option in this case.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">The least restrictive option is there not being a psychiatric treatment order, and to engage voluntarily. I do recognise your concerns, but I think in some</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>situations it might be the case that PTO would provide something that not being on a PTO wouldn't provide. I can't see how that's the case in this situation.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DAVEY:Â  I can. I can see that Wendell knows that he has to attend for</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>treatment, and the onus is on him, and to come down from the mountain to attend, as opposed to people finding him in an undisclosed location. I think the other option there is with a PTO, ifhe does - ifwe do lose him, then we can at least call the police as well. So I think my concern is that this is very oneÂ­ sided. It's putting the treating team in a very difficult position, and I want</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Wendell to have some sort of obligation to come down the mountain.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  He does that every day, Dr Davey.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DAVEY:Â  Into treatment. He does while he is under this.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY: No, he does it every day. He has to. To get water, to get gas for his heater. He comes every day. I've been in touch with him every day, and he has the same routine every day.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  (indistinct)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DAVEY: (indistinct) I think that's right for food, and for social contact, but in order to receive treatment, he's very clever. He's done this for the last seven or eight, or more years. He knows that until we've made this decision</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>that he has to toe the line. The history tells me that he hasn't toed the line once he's gone off the treatment order. That's my concern. I want him to be well, and I want him to function adequately, and healthily and happily. Up until now he hasn't. That's what you have to convince me about.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MS BATES:Â  While he has had this process hanging over his head arguably,</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-25</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">like Dr Drew mentioned earlier (indistinct) he hasn't been under any kind of order since he was released (indistinct) he has expressed, not only verbally but through his actions, a willingness to engage. He has come down - he's been given depot injections which are - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: One in hospital, and one since discharge.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES: Which are invasive. Let's not (indistinct) you know, nobody else has to go through that. He has expressed his willingness to.do that, and to</p><p style="text-align: center;">IO<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>continue to do that. I note you're looking at the history, and that - look, I can't argue against that. There is history that's problematic, but on this occasion, and this is what we need to be primarily looking at, I understand that you need to also look at the history to determine whether or not somebody is going (indistinct) but primarily in this case he has shown a willingness, and expressed</p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>a willingness to consent to continue this treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">I think it would be a far more therapeutic process for him to be engaged voluntarily on this occasion. It's also - I mean, the tribunal has said this before, "This is your last chance," you know? This is - like, "We've given you chances</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>before. You can't just keep doing this. Eventually you're going to be on a psychiatric treatment order." I think given the history - the length oftime he's been engaged with - I think the previous presentation in the ACT was 2013. Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>I think given that time in between, noting that there has been extreme (indistinct) I think it's worthwhile giving him another chance. From a legal point of view I really - I would argue the (indistinct) can be fully demonstrated in this case. I think - which is the key question here. But also I think there is a less restrictive option available, and I think (indistinct) in this case.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">DRDAVEY: Ifitworks. MS BATES: Yes.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DAVEY:Â  There's a I 0-year history of it not working.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  Can I ask a question?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  We might adjourn and discuss it unless</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>anyone wants to make any further comments.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DREW: Can I say one other thing? Can I suggest that very quickly someone from the treatment team goes with Wendell up to see where he does live, and then when you call the police you'll know where to send them.</p><p style="text-align: center;">45</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHI0S/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-26</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: That's a good idea. MS HALSEY: I put my hand up for that.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: On a sunny day. Not a rainy day. Does anyone have any other submissions they'd like to make before we adjourn to consider - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  I just wanted to ask a question because I - I'm not - I didn't read</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>all of the notes, but when he was under a treatment order in Queensland - - - PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: On what occasion?</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  I believe it was 2016.</p><p style="text-align: center;">15</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: 2016, yes. MS MABEY: Yes. Did he - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">20Â  PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: It was revoked on 16 June, because he said he'd take treatment. He was discharged on Olanzapine on 7 July 2016, and that's where the records stop.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  Did you continue treatment after the treatment order?</p><p style="text-align: center;">25</p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I did, yes. I actually already told you about this. When I went to the US, and it was $600 per month. I cannot afford that.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL:Â  Then he came back to - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY:Â  How long did you go to the states for?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH: I was there for six months, then I went to Mexico for one year, and then I came from Mexico to here.</p><p style="text-align: center;">35</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: To Canberra.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DR DAVEY:Â  Which is when you presented to City Mental Health.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  I've been here for four months almost.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MS MABEY: And there's been concerns about his mental state for that time. PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Okay. Ms Bates, do you want to say</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>something before we're adjourned?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-27 .</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MS BATES: In regards to police, even if - if somebody is on a PTO I understand having that piece of paper is helpful, but you can (indistinct) issues. We believe there is a risk, and - - -</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Well, there has already been contact with the AFP, obviously, because that's how he was taken to the hospital, because of concerns with his behaviour at Centrelink.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>MS BATES: So while we can never predict how the police will react in any given situation, noting that there has been (indistinct) incident, they would arguably take this one seriously, regardless of whether a PTO is in place. I think that the police would take it seriously. Thank you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Ms Halsey, I think we understand your position that we shouldn't make an order.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ADJOURNED</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>RESUMED</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(4.23 pm]</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">[4.31 pm]</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: So we're resuming matter MH108 of 2012.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DR DREW: Can I say I'm going to excuse myself. I have another appointment I have to go to, but I've made my position plain to everybody before.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MR NESMITH:Â  Thank you, Dr Drew.</p><p style="text-align: center;">30</p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Look, obviously this is a very difficult decision, and in fact the tribunal is not in agreement about it. Dr Drew has made his view clear, and - that he does not think that it's appropriate to make the psychiatric treatment order, and certainly the most therapeutic situation</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>would be voluntary treatment. I can say the tribunal is in agreement in these respects. We do think that Mr Nesmith has a mental illness.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">We do think that without treatment he is likely to do harm to himself - serious harm as a result of misadventure or self-neglect, and potentially how people</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>may react to him that leads him to risk, and that also, without treatment, his mental state and functioning will seriously deteriorate. So we're satisfied of those things. What the areas of disagreement focus on are the question of whether Mr Nesmith refuses treatment or not. I know we've had a lot of conversation about what practical effect a PTO would have. In my view, that's</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>not particularly relevant. Legally it might be relevant in practical terms, but it's</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHI 08/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-28</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">not part of the legal test. The legal test is actually does he have a mental illness; what's the risk if not treated; and then this key question, is he refusing treatment?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>Both Dr Davies and I are of the view that there should be a treatment order for six months and the reason why is because, when we look at those medical records, we see a history of a person who continually says to the authorities that he will accept treatment and then it all goes wrong and he's not involved in treatment any more. So just for the purposes of remembering that the best</p><p style="text-align: center;">10<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>predictor of future behaviour is past behaviour, the records that we have say that he came self-presented to a hospital in June 2011, and this was in Ballarat, with suicidal ideation. At that stage he had not eaten for six days. He was quite unwell and he was admitted to hospital.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>The latest record from that 2011 episode was 31 August 2011 when it wrote that two weeks post-discharge he was to move to Western Australia, he was referred to the WA Mental Health Service, Swan Mental Health. He was going to be living with a supportive bunch of friends and everything was going to be wonderful, but it didn't work out that way. There was no order made because it</p><p style="text-align: center;">20<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>was all going to be voluntary. It didn't work out because we see that in April 2012 actually he's admitted to the ACT Adult Mental Health Unit, then he's discharged, again voluntary, lost to that service.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">The next thing that happens is he has another admission in Canberra in 2013</p><p style="text-align: center;">25<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>where he came in, as we discussed previously, through the Emergency Department. Again, an opportunity for him to engage voluntarily in treatment, for what we're satisfied is his mental illness, lost to follow-up treatment. Then he ends up in Lismore in 2014. We don't have the records for that but we do have a reference that he says that he spent a week in prison in Grafton. I don't</p><p style="text-align: center;">30<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>know whether that's a reference to being kept in hospital or actually a criminal thing, we don't know. But whatever we know is he didn't stay in treatment after coming in to treatment in Lismore; he was out of it.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">By 12 April 2016 he is in Queensland. He gets admitted after what sounds like</p><p style="text-align: center;">35<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>a very risky episode at a caravan park where he's making comments about young women and that could have led him to being misunderstood and physically threatened. Certainly he was brought in under an emergency order to the hospital. He was put on an involuntary treatment order. That was revoked on 16 June. He was discharged on Olanzapine on 7 July 2016 but</p><p style="text-align: center;">40<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>that's where the records end because he's been lost to treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">We are satisfied on the basis of that record that no matter what Mr Nesmith says and how persuasive he is and genuine - Mr Nesmith, I think you're genuine, and so does Dr Davies, when you tell us you're going to engage in</p><p style="text-align: center;">45<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>treatment. It's not that we think you're lying to us, we think you're absolutely</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MHl 08/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-29</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">honest and genuine, but life interferes with that. But we're confident that with a psychiatric treatment order, because you are a good person and a</p><p style="text-align: center;">rule-conscious person you will comply with that and you won't be lost to treatment while that order is in place.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5</p><p style="text-align: center;">So we're going to make an order for six months and we'll review that before it expires and we look forward to hearing what your accommodation turns out being like when we review this. It might be that you're still living where you're living now because you might choose to do that, and that's fine, or you might</p><p style="text-align: center;">IO<span style="white-space: pre;">		</span>choose to go into other accommodation. That's fine too. But what's really important is we're ordering that you will continue with the recommended medical treatment for another six months and we'll hear how that's going at the end of those six months. Okay?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">15<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>MR NESMITH:Â  Thank you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">PRESIDENT MEMBER DANIEL: Thank you.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MATTER ADJOURNED AT 4.38 PM ACCORDINGLY</p><p style="text-align: center;">20</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">.MH108/12 02.08.18<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>P-30</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">File Number</p><p style="text-align: center;">MHÂ  I</p><p style="text-align: center;">ACT CIVIL AND ADMINISTRATIVE</p><p style="text-align: center;">.TRIBUNAL</p><p style="text-align: center;">MENTAL HEALTH ORDERS</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">APPLICATION !=ORM !=OR PSYCHIATRIC TREATMENT ORDER, COMMUNITY CARE ORDER AND/OR RESTRICTION ORDER</p><p style="text-align: center;">I.AG.AT</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">/IUSlIW.1/\N OAPITALTEJlllffORY Â·</p><p style="text-align: center;">ON.t& /1.t>M!NISlJWlVETRIDUtw..</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">F.or use by relevant person under Mental /-lea/th Aot 2015</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">1, This application Is about: Name: Wendell Charles Nesmith</p><p style="text-align: center;">Gender: Male<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>DOE!: 27/06/1984</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">2, The application ls made by (Chief Psychiatrist or delegate or nominee of the Chief Psychiatrist):</p><p style="text-align: center;">Name: Dr Emma Glanville</p><p style="text-align: center;">(Â  _-<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Position held: Consultant Psychiatrist</p><p style="text-align: center;">Report written by Dr Caroline Flynn, Registrar</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">3,Â  Â Wfiy are 966 trfakfitgi:h1s applffiffl.1'6'ft?1mcrtb levar1t evei1Eil'e'atlfii'fttiffffuiijjpllcatlon)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Mr Nesmith Is a 33 yo homeless, unemployed gentleman who was referred to our service by his GP on the 15/5/18 and seen my our mental health cllnlclans on several occasions before his psychiatry assessment on 6th June 2018,</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Mr Nesmlth's Initial presentation wascharacterized by quite odd and eccentric beliefs and preoccupations, and grandiose themes, These manifested more floridly on the l't June 2018 with concerns he had an untreated psychosis with manlcfeatures and an appointment made with Dr Flynn (registrar). Mr Nesmith consistently Insists that he does not believe he has a mental Illness nor needing any antipsychotlc or other psychiatric medications. our concerns are for his long-term welfare If he remains chronically unwell, and associated risks discussed In more detail In sections to follow.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MENTAL ILLNESS OR MENTAL DISORDER (Use the definitions set out In the glossary at the end of this form)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">4. The person has a mental illness</p><p style="text-align: center;">mental disorder</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">xYes<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>o No</p><p style="text-align: center;">oYes<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>x No</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">and/or a</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">For mental Illness: Describe how the illness Impairs the person's mental functioning, Identify the areas of function Ing that are affected by the Illness and Identify the symptoms that characterise the Illness and/or the behaviour that may be taken to indicate the presence of one or more of the symptoms.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">In presentations and assessments on the 1'' June and 6th June It Is apparent that Mr Nesmith hasa psychotic</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Created By: Dr Caroline Flynn (Registrar) Printed ByÂ·: Dr Caroline Flynn (Registrar)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Page 3 of 14Â·</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Illness characterized by an elaborate, systemlzed delusional system that Is very fixed, and possibly on a background of a sch/zotyp,al personality disorder, with long-standing beliefs and suspicion about several organizatio