f\llr Nesmith does not believe his has a mental Illness, and that anyone who questions his beliefs or</span></p><p style="text-align: center;">Â·Â·Â·Â·Â·Â·Â·Â·-<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Â·-Â·--Â·Â·"â€¢â€¢Â·-Â·J.ntmtlqlis Isp_artotthewlge-spJe4cl.censorshlpffed cover-up2, Jie.al.Â§Q.i;,elleves.mgdlcal staff enforce,,_._.</p><p style="text-align: center;">their own views of societal norms and !llness In a biased way and with Ill-Intent, Any discussion of mental Illness or offer of antlpsychotlc medication Is seen as us being Judgemental, dismissive, and at worse, part of the c nsplracy to keep him from doing hls tasks of saving humanity from various threats, He has a hint of Insight than he can get "busy" and elevated, but only wants "Xanax" (alprazolam) to help slow him down, Â·He believes this Is part of his excitable personality style and not a sign of a mood or psychotic disorder, The notion ofgo!ng to hospital for treatment Is also seen as the ultimate punishment alas, and he would find this very traumatic and coercive and further proof of the medical establishments malevolence, This belief ls also based on real past negative experiences with Involuntary psychiatric admissions and side effects from several antipsychotics that he reports,</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">REFUSAL</p><p style="text-align: center;">. 6, Does the person refuse to receive treatment, care or support; or, If the person has decision-making capacity, refuse to consent to treatment, care or support?</p><p style="text-align: center;">Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  IBlYos<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>D No If yes, describe what the person does and/or says that constitutes refusal</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Mr Nesmith )s refusing to trial any antlpsychot!c medication due to his conviction that he does not have a mental Illness and that any treatment will be unjust, unfounded and cause harm,</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">RISI( OR DETERIORATION (answer on basis of likelihood If untreated)</p><p style="text-align: center;">7, Is the person doing, or likely to do serious harm to them'.elves or someone else because of the mental</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Created By: Dr Caroline Flynn (Registrar) Printed By: Dr Camline Flynn (Registrar)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Page 9 of 14</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Illness or mental disorder?<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>IBJYes ? No</p><p style="text-align: center;">Is the person suffering, or likely to suffer serious mental or physical deterioration because of the mental Illness or mental disorder?<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>IBJYes<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Â· ? No</p><p style="text-align: center;">Jfyes, explain your reasons for this opinion.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Risk prediction is a fraught area as clinicians cannot be precise or quantltate risk given the variables and unpredictable nature of people's behaviour and their environments.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">However, the risks to Mr Nesmith Include that the longer he Is left with an untreated psychotic Illness the worse his prognosis and quality of recovery, that could have devastating Impacts on his ability to work, have relationships, Jive and function In society. There Is a potential risk of him falsely Identifying a community member as the "grandmaster" of the Freemasons based on a delusion, and conflict arising with possible violent sequelae