 style="text-align: center;">Notes: Applications for Interim or other Orders</p><p style="text-align: center;">This form may be used1111en an appllcafion has already commenced before Iha Tnbunal and a par\Y or someone else vAsheslo'apply for anlntenm or other order In relation to !hat application. ltshould be used only when no other specific form e sls for!he appllcallon.</p><p style="text-align: center;">The person submitting this notice must give acopy to every other party.to ihe application. A person who wishes to apply for an lnlertm or other orderIn an application should ensure!hat ever;par\Y to!he appllcatlon Is aware of what ordern are sought and when the appllcallon Is going to be made, and should expect to attend and give evidence bafora !heTribunal, or file an allidavlt In support of!his application,</p><p style="text-align: center;">In making a decl on about how an application for an lntertm or other order should be made In amatter Iha1Jibunal will consider:</p><p style="text-align: center;">a. !he nead to obse,ve natural justice and procedural fairness: and</p><p style="text-align: center;">b, !he requirement forprocedures to be _as simple, quick, lnaxpenslve and Informal as Is consistent with achle ng Jusllce; and</p><p style="text-align: center;">c. !he needs of !he parijcular matter.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">IN THE AUSTRALIAN CAPITAL TERRITORY CIVIL AND ADMINISTRATIVE TRIBUNAL</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell Charles Nesmith</p><p style="text-align: center;">Appellant and</p><p style="text-align: center;">ACT Chief Psychiatrist</p><p style="text-align: center;">Respondent</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">AA 42/2018</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">SUBMISSION IN RESPECT OF THE APPELLANT'S WEBSITE</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">1. The Respondent does not oppose the Appeal Tribunal accessing the Appellant's website before the hearing for the purpose of assessing its content.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Procedural History</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">2. By email to the Respondent and the Tribunal dated 25 October 2018, the Appellant indicated he wished to submit his "the entire site of nesmith.net into evidence" in the appeal.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">3. By email dated 26 October 2018, the Appeal Tribunal invited the Respondent to make written submissions about whether it should access the website before the hearing for the purpose of assessing its content. The Appeal Tribunal indicated that it has not yet ruled on whether to admit the contents of the Appellant's website into evidence in the appeal.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Nature of the appeal and the power to admit new evidence</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">4. Section 79(3) of the ACT Civil and Administrative Tribunal Act 2008 (ACAT Act) provides that a party to an original application that has been decided by the Tribunal may appeal that decision on a question of law or fact.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5. Section 82 of the ACAT Act permits the Appeal Tribunal, as it considers appropriate, to deal with the appeal:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(a) as a new application; or</p><p style="text-align: center;">(b) as a review of all or part of the original decision.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">6. The Tribunal has indicated that the appeal hearing will proceed under s 82(b) as a review of the original decision (Directions, 24 September 2018; email of26 October 2018).</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Filed for the Respondent by:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ACT Government Solicitor</p><p style="text-align: center;">Contact:</p><p style="text-align: center;">Kate Smyth</p><p style="text-align: center;">Level 5, 12 Moore Street</p><p style="text-align: center;">Tel:</p><p style="text-align: center;">(02) 6207 6483</p><p style="text-align: center;">CANBERRA CITY ACT 2601</p><p style="text-align: center;">Fax:</p><p style="text-align: center;">(02) 6207 0650</p><p style="text-align: center;">PO Box 260, CIVIC SQUARE ACT 2608</p><p style="text-align: center;">Email:</p><p style="text-align: center;">kate.smyth@act.gov.au</p><p style="text-align: center;">DX 5602 CANBERRA</p><p style="text-align: center;">Ref:</p><p style="text-align: center;">635075</p><p style="text-align: center;">7. In an appeal by way ofreview under s 82(b) of the ACAT Act:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ the Appellant must demonstrate an e!Tor of fact or law, or an erroneous exercise of discretion; and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ the Appeal Tribunal may receive futther evidence.1</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">8. The Respondent submits that the factors relevant to determining whether to admit further evidence in an appeal by way ofreview include:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(a) Whether exceptional circumstances exist that wairnnt the admission offu1ther evidence, in light of the need for :finality in litigation.2 The exceptional circutnstances test was stated by the High Court in Fox v Percy (2003) 214 CLR 118 (at [22]) in respect of appeals to the NSW Supreme Coutt. It has been adopted in respect of appeals within ACAT in appellate decisions of the Tribunal and the ACT Supreme Court;3</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(b) Whether the further evidence is relevant to the grout1ds of appeal in that it will assist the Appeal Tribunal to decide whether there was any e!Toi" in the decisionÂ· under review.4 This may include considering:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(i) whether the evidence relates to facts that existed at the time the decision under appeal was made, as evidence that goes to facts that post-date the decision is less likely to be relevant to whether there was any e1Tor in the decision;5 and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(ii) whether the evidence is in the nature of an expert opinion on relevant issues;6 a11d</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(c) Whether the paity seeking leave to present the futther evidence had the oppottunity to present that evidence at the hearing at :first instance (or put another way, whether there was any breach of procedural fairness to the patty at</p><p style="text-align: center;">:first instance);7 and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(d) Whether the admission of the fu1ther evidence would require even futther evidence still to properly assess the weight to be afforded to it (for example,</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">1 See Rule 21(c) of the ACT Civil and Administrative Tribunal Procedure Rules 2009 (No 2); Excel Intelligent Pty Ltd v Thomson (Appeal) [2018] ACAT 4 (Excel), [46]-[55] and ACT Supreme Court decisions cited there, including Giusida Pty Limitedv Commissioner/or ACT Revenue [2016] ACTSC 275, B&T Constructions (AC1; Ply Ltdv Construction Occupations Registrar and the Owners- Units Plan 3324 [2013] ACTSC 291 (B&T Co11structio11s) and The Legal Practitioner v Council of the Law Society of the</p><p style="text-align: center;">ACT [2011] ACTSC 207; Brentv Road Transport Authority (Appeal) [2018] ACAT 37, [39]; In the matter of AB (Appeal) [2018] ACAT 18 (AB), [21], [41]; Colquhoun Mwphy Poâ€¢Ltdv Reddy (Appeal) [2018] ACAT 42 (Colq11ho1111 M11rphy), [8]; The Tenant v Commissioner/or Social Housing (Appeal) [2016] ACAT 49, [8]-[16],</p><p style="text-align: center;">2 In respect of the need for finality, see AB [20] and Colquhoun Murphy, [35].</p><p style="text-align: center;">3 Excel [52]; AB [21]; Colquhoun Mwphy, [38]; B&T ConsnÂ·uctions, [13]-[14].</p><p style="text-align: center;">4 Colquhoun Mwphy, [46]; AB [26], [38].</p><p style="text-align: center;">5 AB [22]-[23], [25]-[26], citing Fe/le & Commissioner/or Social Housing in theACT[2012] ACAT 82, [27].</p><p style="text-align: center;">6 Excel, [61]-[62].</p><p style="text-align: center;">7 Colquhoun Mwphy, [42] (the Appeals Tribunal did not grant leave to tender further evidence on the basis</p><p style="text-align: center;">of a breach of procedural fairness, but appeared to treat the breach as a relevant consideration).</p><p style="text-align: center;">2</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">where the proposed evidence comprises statements of third parties and its admission may require cross-examination of the makers of those statements).8</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">9. The Appellant's website contains a substantial volume of material. He has not identified how auy or all of this material relates to the grounds of appeal stated in his Application for Appeal filed on 7 September 2018.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">10. The Respondent reserves its position on whether the Appeal Tribunal should grant the Appellant leave to tender his website into evidence, The Respondent will address this in its main submission (as per the Appeal's.Tribunal directions of24 September 2018).</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">11. However, as a question arises as to the relevance of the material contained on the Appellant's website, the Respondent does not object to the Appeals Tribunal examining that material to form a view on whether it should be admitted.9</p><p style="text-align: center;">(</p><p style="text-align: center;">...Â  . <span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>..............................)<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>,.</p><p style="text-align: center;">ACT Government Solicitor (per Kate Smyth)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">2 November 2018</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">8 Colquhoun Mwphy, [36]-[37], [45].</p><p style="text-align: center;">9 Evidence Act 201J, s 58(1). The Appeals Tribunal need not comply with the rules of evidence (ACAT Act, s 8) but they may provide useful guidance.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">IN THE AUSTRALIAN CAPITAL TERRITORY CIVIL AND ADMINISTRATIVE TRIBUNAL</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell Charles Nesmith</p><p style="text-align: center;">Appellant and</p><p style="text-align: center;">ACT Chief Psychiatrist</p><p style="text-align: center;">Respondent</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">RESPONDENT'S SUBMISSIONS</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">1. The ACT Chief Psychiatrist (Respondent) seeks orders that the appeal be dismissed and the Tribunal's decision of2 August 2018 be confirmed.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Background</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">2. On 2 August 2018, the Tribunal (the Original Tribunal) made a Psychiatric Treatment Order (PTO) in relation to the Appellant for a period of 6 months, following hearings on 12 July 2018 and 2 August 2018.1</p><p style="text-align: center;">3. The Tribunal's power to make a PTO is set out ins 58 of the Mental Health Act 2015</p><p style="text-align: center;">(Mental Health Act) as follows:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">58<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>Psychiatric treatment order</p><p style="text-align: center;">(I) This section applies to-</p><p style="text-align: center;">(a) a person assessed under an assessment order; or</p><p style="text-align: center;">(b) a person in relation to whom an application for a mental health order has been made</p><p style="text-align: center;">under part 5.2; or</p><p style="text-align: center;">(<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>(c) a person in relation to whom an application for a forensic mental health order has been made under division 7.1.2; or</p><p style="text-align: center;">(d) a person required by a court to submit to the jurisdiction of the ACAT nuder the Crimes Act, part 13 or the Crimes Act 1914 (Cwlth), patt IB.</p><p style="text-align: center;">(2) The ACAT may make a psychiatric treatment order in relation to the person ifÂ­</p><p style="text-align: center;">(a) the person has a mental illness; and</p><p style="text-align: center;">(b) eithe1</p><p style="text-align: center;">(i) the person does not have decision-making capacity to consent to the treatment, care or</p><p style="text-align: center;">support and refuses to receive the hÂ·eatment care or support; or</p><p style="text-align: center;">(ii) the person has decision-making capacity to consent to the treatment, care or support,</p><p style="text-align: center;">but refuses to consent; and</p><p style="text-align: center;">(c) the ACAT believes on reasonable grounds that, because of the mental illness, the</p><p style="text-align: center;">person-</p><p style="text-align: center;">(i) is doing, or is likely to do, serious harm to themself or someone else; or</p><p style="text-align: center;">(ii) is suffering, or is likely to suffer, serious mental or physical deterioration; and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">1 The Application for a PTO in respect of the Appellant (MH 108/2012) first came before the Tribunal prior to 12 July 20 I8, but was adjourned to that date so the Appellant could be present: Transcript, 12 July 2018,</p><p style="text-align: center;">pp. 3-4.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(d) in relation to a person mentioned in paragraph (b) (ii)-the ACAT is satisfied that the harm or deterioration, or likely harm or deterioration, mentioned in paragraph (c) is of such a serious nature that it outweighs the person's right to refuse to consent; and</p><p style="text-align: center;">(e) the ACAT is satisfied that psychiatric treatment, care or support is likelyto-</p><p style="text-align: center;">(i) reduce the harm or deterioration, or the likelihood of the harm or deterioration, mentioned in paragraph (c); or</p><p style="text-align: center;">(ii) result in an improvement in the person's psychiatric condition; and</p><p style="text-align: center;">(f) if an application has been made for a forensic mental health order-the ACAT is satisfied that a psychiatric treatment order should be made instead; and</p><p style="text-align: center;">(g) the ACAT is satisfied that the treatment, care or supp01t to be provided under the psychiatric treatment order cannot be adequately provided in another way that would involve less restriction of the freedom of choice and movement of the person.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">4. The Appellant is a person in respect of whom a PTO may be made under s 58(1)(b). The findings of the Original Tribunal, as set out in its Statement dated 2 August 2018, match closely the te1ms of s 58(2) of the Mental Health Act. In particular, the Original Tribunal found that:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ the Appellant has a mental illness;</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ the Appellant does not have decision-malcing capacity to consent to the treatment, care or support proposed for him;</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ the Appellant refused the treatment proposed for him:</p><p style="text-align: center;">because although he says he will accept treatment and in the very recent past has been accepting treatment; he has a 7 year history of ceasing treatment after advising health authorities he will continue with treatment. The Tribunal considers his cunent compliance with treatment is of a short duration and against the extensive history is of the view that he refuses treatment (Statement, (a)(iv));</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ there are reasonable grounds to believe that the Appellant, because of his mental illness:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">o is likely to do serious haim to himself as a result of misadventure or self-neglect when unwell; and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">o is likely to suffer serious deterioration of his mental state and functioning if untreated;</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ psychiatric treatment, care or support is likely to reduce the likelihood ofhaim or deterioration and is likely to result in an improvement of the Appellant's psychiatric condition; and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ the treatment proposed under the PTO could not be adequately provided in another way that would involve less restriction of the Appellant's :freedom of choice and movement.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">5. The Original Tribunal's decision was made by majority. The Psychiatrist Member was of the view that a PTO should not be made.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">6. The documentary evidence before the Original Tribunal comprised:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ the application for a PTO by Dr Emma Glanville, Consultant Psychiatrist (as delegate or nominee of the Chief Psychiatrist) dated 19 June 2018; and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ records obtained from the Chief Psychiatrist from mental health services in Victoria (Ballarat) and QLD (Caims) in respect of the Appellant's prior admissions in those jurisdictions.</p><p style="text-align: center;">7. The Tribunal heard evidence from the following persons who attended the hearings on 12 July and/or 2 August 2018:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ the Appellant;</p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ Dr Reagan O'Neil and Mr Kel Thomas from the Adult Mental Health Unit at The Canbe1Ta Hospital (TCH);</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ Ms Julie Hanson and Ms Kate Mabey from City Mental Health; and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ Ms Chris Halsey from the Public Advocate.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Facts</p><p style="text-align: center;">8. In summary, the evidence before the Tribunal established the following facts.</p><p style="text-align: center;">9. The Appellant moved to Australia from the US as a teenager. In around 2010, after his marriage ended, he returned to the US for some time.2</p><p style="text-align: center;">10. The Appellant moved back to Australia in 2011. On 21 June 2011 he presented to Ballarat Health Services, following a refe1Tal from a GP to whom he had disclosed a specific plan to commit suicide on his birthday on 27 June 2011. He was homeless and living in the bush. He had not eaten for 6 days upon his arrival in Ballarat in around May/June 2011. He reported previous psychiatric admission in WA although the details are unclear.3 He was voluntarily admitted to the Adult Acute Unit in Ballarat on the basis that he had a significant delusional disorder with schizotypal personality issues.4</p><p style="text-align: center;">11. The Appellant was discharged from hospital in Ballarat on 26 June 2011 and subsequently seen as anoutpatient until his case was closed on 31 August 2011. Around that time, he moved to Pe1th to reside with friends and he was refen-ed to a local mental health service tltere. Upon discharge, his treating clinician in Ballarat stated that the Appellant had poor insight and did not agree with the diagnosis of schizophrenia.5 He was rated as at moderate risk of accidental or deliberate self-harm, and low risk ofhaim to others but vulnerable to harm from others. He was assessed as being at high risk of non-compliance with treatment.6</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">2 QLD Government Mental Health Services (Athe1ton MHS), Consumer Care Review Summary and Plan, 7 July 2016, ("Cairns Care Review"), p. 2.</p><p style="text-align: center;">3 Ballarat Health Services, Psychiatric Services Intake Assessment, 21 June 2011 ("Ballarat Intake</p><p style="text-align: center;">Assessment"), p. 4.</p><p style="text-align: center;">4 Ballarat Intake Assessment, p. 15,</p><p style="text-align: center;">5 Ballarat Health Services, Psychiatric Services Case Closure, 31 August 2011 ("Ballarat Case Closure"),</p><p style="text-align: center;">pp. 3, 5,</p><p style="text-align: center;">6 Ballarat Case Closure, pp. 4, 5.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">12. On 28 April 2012, following a refe1Tal from a GP who believed he had schizotypal personality disorder, the Appellant was involuntarily admitted to the adult mental health unit at The Canbe1Ta Hospital (TCH). He was discharged on 5 May 2012. A PTO was not made (as he was not floridly psychotic) and he subsequently lost contact with services.7</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">13. In 2013, the Appellant was briefly placed on an emergency detention order after he presented at TCH with grandiose and disordered thoughts and requiring surgical intervention because he had inserted a speaker wire into his penis. He was discharged within several days as he presented as more settled with no evidence of psychosis. He subsequently lost contact with services.8</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">14. In around 2013, the Appellant spent a week in "prison" in Grafton, on his account after he tried to mn for prime minister and the government didn't lilce it.9 The Appellant was admitted to psychiatric care in Lismore in 201310 or 2014.11</p><p style="text-align: center;">15. On 12 April 2016 the Appellant was admitted to the Cairns Mental Health Unit in a floridly psychotic state after he had made sexually inappropriate comments about young girls at a caravan park, stating that he wanted to many a virgin.12 He was made the subject of an involuntary treatment order. He was discharged on 6 May 2016 and seen as an outpatient. He willingly engaged with mental health services and was compliant with his medication after discharge. On 16 June 2016 the Involuntary Treatment Order was revoked.13 He was last seen on 5 July 2016 at which time he reported plans to return to the US.14</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">16. The Appellant spent around 18 months in the US and Mexico before comingÂ·to Canberra in around May 2018.15 Shortly after his anival, a GP refe1Ted him to the City Mental Health team.16 He was seen on 15 May, 1 June and 6 June 2018.17 He voluntarily engaged with mental health services, apparently at least in part because he needed support to establish his eligibility for a Centrelink disability suppmt pension.18 He presented as grandiose and delusional. He did not accept that he has a mental illness and he refused to be admitted to hospital for treatment or take anti-psychotic</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">7 ACAT Mental Health Orders Application Form, 19 June 2018 ("PTO Application"), p.8</p><p style="text-align: center;">8 PTO Application, p.8.</p><p style="text-align: center;">9 Cairns Care Review Summa1y, p. 4; QLD Government Mental Health Services (Cairns MHlJ), Consumer End of Care I Discharge Summaty, 11 May 2016 ("Cairns Discharge Summary"), p. 2. It is not clear if the reference to prison is a correctional facility or a secure mental health unit.</p><p style="text-align: center;">10 Cairns and Hinterland Hospital and Health Services District, Assessments (Dr Jan Steel, 11 Aptil 2016 and Dr Vukov, 12 April 2016)("Cairns Psychiatrist Review"), p. 1.</p><p style="text-align: center;">11 Cairns Care Review Summary, p. 2. It is not clear on the records if his treatment in Lismore was following his</p><p style="text-align: center;">'<imprisonment" in Grafton or a separate episode.</p><p style="text-align: center;">12 Cairns Care Review Summary, p. 2; Cairns DischatÂ·ge Summary, pp 2-3; QLD Government Mental Health</p><p style="text-align: center;">Services, Progress Notes, 12 April 2016 ("Cairns ED Review Progress Notes"), p. 1.</p><p style="text-align: center;">13 Caisos Care Review, p, 3.</p><p style="text-align: center;">14 QLD Government, Progress Notes, Outpatient, 9 June 2016 and 5 July 2016 ("Cairns Outpatient Progress</p><p style="text-align: center;">Notes"), p. 1.</p><p style="text-align: center;">15 Transcript, 2 August 2018, p. 27</p><p style="text-align: center;">16 PTO Application, p. 3; Transcript, 2 August 2018, p. 9.</p><p style="text-align: center;">17 PTO Application, p. 3.</p><p style="text-align: center;">18 Transcript, 12 July 2018, pp. 5-6.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">medications.19 Accordingly, on 19 June 2018, an application for a PTO was made on behalf of the Chief Psychiatrist.</p><p style="text-align: center;">17. On 4 July 2018, the Appellant was admitted to the Adult Mental Health Unit at TCH under an emergency assessment order after displaying highly agitated and aggressive behaviours towards staff at a Centrelinlc office, which had resulted in police being called.20 On his admission he was agitated, aggressive, manic and highly labile, and he had intense, very well-systemised delusional beliefs.21 He initially I'efused medication but was given intramuscular anti-psychotics and subsequently agreed to talce an injection of Olanzapine. His presentation was much improved by the first hearing before the Original Tribunal on 12 July 2018.22 On 17 July 2018, the Appellant was discharged from TCH.</p><p style="text-align: center;">18. On 2 August 2018, the Original Tribunal made the PTO.</p><p style="text-align: center;">19. On 7 September 2018, the Appellant filed an Application for Appeal, together with an application to extend the time for lodging an appeal, which was granted by consent.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20. The Appellant has not filed any further documents in support of his appeal, although he has indicated he wishes to tender new evidence (see below).</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Appellant's grounds of appeal</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">21. The Appellant's grounds of appeal state that the Original Tribunal erred in making the PTO because there was insufficient evidence or no evidence before the Original Tribunal to satisfy the following requirements of s 58(2) of the Mental Health Act:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ that the Appellant was refusing treatment (s 58(2)(b)(ii))(Ground 1); and/or</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ that the Appellant was a serious risk to himself or others, or that he was at risk of deterioration (s 58(2)(c)(i) and (ii))(Ground 2).</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Respondent's submissions on admission of new evidence</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">22. The Respondent does not seek to rely on new evidence at the appeal hearing.</p><p style="text-align: center;">23. The Appellant indicated by emails dated 25 and 26 October 2018 to the Tribunal that he wishes to submit his website "nesmith.net" (in particular the section on "Rebirthing") into evidence on appeal.</p><p style="text-align: center;">24. The Respondent reiterates its submission of2 November 2018 that new evidence should only be admitted in an appeal by way of rehearing under s 82(b) of the ACT Civil and Administrative Tribunal Act 2008 (ACAT Act) in exceptional circumstances. The Appellant has not identified exceptional circumstances that warrant the admission of the material on the "Rebirthing" section of the website as new evidence on appeal.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">19PTO Application, p. 9; Transcript, 12 July 2018, pp. 6-7.</p><p style="text-align: center;">20 Transcript, 12 July 2018, pp. 7, 11.</p><p style="text-align: center;">21 Transcript, 12 July 2018, pp. 11-13.</p><p style="text-align: center;">22 Transcript, 12 July 2018, pp. 11-12.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25. The material on the Appellant's website (to the extent reviewed by the Respondent) traverses a range of themes, most of which have no apparent relevance to his appeal (including, for example, explanations by the Appellant of his practices in making videos, animated footage concerning religious themes and records of his interactions with Facebook). In paiis the website discloses the Appellant's experiences of mental health treatment and his objections to the mental health system and services.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">26. The Tribunal should only admit new evidence where it is relevant, meaning that it could rationally affect (directly or indirectly) the assessment of theprobability of the existence of a fact in issue in the proceeding.23 The material on the Appellant's website, even insofaiÂ· as it concerns the mental health system, is not likely to rationally affect the Tribunal's assessment of whether any of the grounds of appeal me made out. The fact that the Appellant had objections to mental health treatment (especially as an inpatient) was apparent on the evidence before the Original T1ibunal, and his historic non-compliance with treatment was a reason for the making of the PTO. The website material does not add to this in a new or substantial way. The Respondent submits that it is for the Appellant to aiticulate how the website material relates specifically to his grounds of appeal, beyond generalised asseiiions that it exposes "c01Tuption" and "evil" in the mental health system.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">27. No breach of procedural fairness arises to the Appellant if the material is not admitted. Much of the material pmp01is to pre-date the Original Tribunal's decision. The Appellant could have sought to tender this material at first instance but he did not do so. To the extent that it post-dates the Original Tribunal's decision, it is unlikely to be capable of revealing any error in that decision.24</p><p style="text-align: center;">28. The Respondent accordingly submits that the Tribunal should not admit the Appellant's website (in whole or in part) into evidence on the appeal.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">29. In the alternative, should the Appellant's website (in whole or in paii) be admitted into evidence, the Respondent submits that it does not demonstrate any error of fact or law in the decision of the original Tribunal. To the contraiÂ·y, the Appellant's website is consistent with the Tribunal's findings that he has a mental illness and he is not inclined to volnntaiÂ·ily consent to treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Respondent's submissions on grounds of appeal</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Overview</p><p style="text-align: center;">30. It is axiomatic that the Tribunal is one oflimited jurisdiction, defined by statute.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">31. It is axiomatic that a right of appeal depends on the te1ms of the statute.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">32. Section 79 of the ACAT Act confers a right on a paiiy to a decision by the Tribunal at first instance to appeal from such a decision, but only on a "question of fact or law".</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">23 Evidence Act 2011, s 55(1).</p><p style="text-align: center;">24 In the matter of AB (Appeal) [2018] ACAT 18 (AB), [22]-[23],[25-[26].</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">33. Section 82 confers a discretion on the Appeal Tribunal to determine whether an appeal made under section 79 should be dealt with as a new application or as a review.</p><p style="text-align: center;">34. The jurisdiction or authority of the Appeal Tribunal is confined to matters raising a question of fact or law and that it must therefore be satisfied that a question of fact or law is identified before it proceeds to consider how to deal with an appeal:</p><p style="text-align: center;">(1) section 79 must be satisfied before section 82 can be applied; and</p><p style="text-align: center;">(2) section 82 must be applied with regard to the te1ms and effect of section 79.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">JUl'isdiction</p><p style="text-align: center;">35. The jurisdiction of the Tribunal in an appeal has been the subject of close consideration in previous decisions of the Tribunal and in several decisions of the Supreme Court.</p><p style="text-align: center;">36. A party to an application decided by the Tribunal (an "original application") has a right to appeal the decision to the Tribunal (which we describe as an "Appeal Tribunal"), but it is not a right to appeal at large-it is aright to appeal "on a question of fact or law".25</p><p style="text-align: center;">37. What may be a "question of fact or law" has been the subject of extensive consideration in a number of decisions. The principles were summarised by Refshauge J in City Hill Ltd (ACN 064 633 558 v ACT Planning and Land Authority & Anor [2015] ACTSC 40 who indicated that a question of fact or law "should be formulated in a way that makes very clear what the question oflaw is that arose in the appeal and not either a question that may be one of fact or of mixed fact and law, or that requires a broad inquiry into the constrnction and operation of legislation, none of which are questions of law".26</p><p style="text-align: center;">38. His Honour later noted that while the requirement to identify a question of fact or law was an important consideration in the jurisdiction of a court or tribunal on an appeal, there was no particular form that a question should talce; it was sufficient that there be a "clear and precise identification of a question in a meaningful and intelligible way".27 Conversely, if the grounds of an application do not truly raise a question of fact or law, the defect cannot be cured by using plnÂ·ases like "did the tribunal ell"" or "was it open".28</p><p style="text-align: center;">39. The question of fact or law is not only an important factor in determining jurisdiction, or the authority to decide an application, it is a key factor in the exercise of jurisdiction. The question of fact or law ultimately determines the very subject matter of the appeal.29</p><p style="text-align: center;">40. Accordingly, it is clear that in an appeal by way of review under s 82(b) of the ACAT Act, the Appellant must demonstrate an e11"or of fact or law (which may include an erroneous exercise of discretion).30 As a previous Appeal Tribunal has observed:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">25 ACT Civil and Administrative Trib11nal Act 2008, s 79(3).</p><p style="text-align: center;">26 City Hill Ltd (ACN 064 633 558vACT Planning and Land A11thority &Anor [2015] ACTSC 40 (at [27]).</p><p style="text-align: center;">21 Giusida Ply Limitedv Commissioner/or ACT Reve1111e [2016] ACTSC 275 (Gius/1/a ACTSC) at [26]</p><p style="text-align: center;">28 Birdseye v Australian Sec11rities and Investments Commission [2003] FCAFC 232.</p><p style="text-align: center;">29 TNT Sl9pak International (Aust) Pty Ltdv Commissioner a/Taxation (Cth) (1988) 19 ATR 1067 at 1069-</p><p style="text-align: center;">1070; Comcare v Etheridge (2006) 149 FCR 522 at 527[13]-[15].</p><p style="text-align: center;">30 Excel Intefligent Pty Ltd v Thomson (Appeal) [2018] ACAT 4 (Excel), [46]-[55] and ACT Supreme Cou1t decisions cited there, including Gi11sida Pty Limited v Commissioner/or ACT Revenue [2016] ACTSC 275</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">The appellant cannot merely request the re-exercise of a discretion. The purpose of the appeal process is not to allow an applicant to try and have a matter reheard because they do not like the previous decision. If that were so there would be no point in the original hearing.31</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">A question of fact or a question of law?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">41. The distinction between questions of fact and law can be vexed and there is no one universal test.32 The distinction is arguably not critical when an appeal may be brought on questions of fact or law.33 However, the following general principles are relevant to the present case.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">42. The con-ect construction of a statutory provision is a question of law.34 The question of whether there was no evidence to make a paiticular finding of fact is also one of law.35 The question of whether facts fully found fall within a statutory provision properly construed is generally a question of law.36 However, where a statutory provision uses words according to their ordinary meaning (as opposed to a technical or specialised meaning), and the question is whether facts as found fall within the ordinai-y meaning, and where it is reasonably open to hold that they do (i.e. where there is no one correct answer), then the question of whether they do or not is one offact.37</p><p style="text-align: center;">This appeal</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">43. An appeal does not automatically proceed as a fresh application.38 However, principles appear not to have been established to detennine when an application can so proceed.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">44. The respondent submits the conect approach to be taken in applying these provisions is that which was suggested in The Medical Practitioner and the Act Medical Board (Occupational Discipline) [2010] ACAT 63. In that case, the Appeal Tribunal refe1rnd tothe Coal andAllied Operations Pty Ltd v Australian Industrial Relations Commission (2000) 203 CLR 194 at 203. In Coal and Allied Operations, the High Court examined a provision in a statute which permitted appeal from a vaiÂ·iety of different decisions.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(Gi11s/da ACTSC); B&T Constructions (ACT) Pty Ltd v Construction Occupatfons Registrar and the Owners - Units Plan 3324 [2013] ACTSC 219 (B&T Co11str11ctio11s) and The Legal Practitioner v Council of the Law Society of the ACT [2011] ACTSC 207; Brent v Road TiÂ·ansport Authority (Appeal) [2018] ACAT 37, [39]; AB, [21], [41]; Colquhoun Mwphy PtyLtdv Reddy (Appeal) [2018] ACAT 42 (Colq11ho1111 M11rphy), [8]; The</p><p style="text-align: center;">Tenantv Commissioner/or Social Housing (Appeal) [2016] ACAT 49, [8]-[16].</p><p style="text-align: center;">31 Excel, [48] (internal footnotes omitted).</p><p style="text-align: center;">32 Collector of Customs v Agfa Gevaert Ltd (1996) 186 CLR 389 (Agfa Gevaert), 394; John Flynn Community Group Inc. and Flynn PrimalJ' School Parents and Citizens Association Inc v ACT Heritage Council [2012] ACTSC 50 (Joftu Fly1111) and authorities cited therein, [15].</p><p style="text-align: center;">33 Paan Investments PO, Ltd (In Liq11idation) v Commissionerfor Reven11efor the ACT [2014] ACTSC 161, [54].</p><p style="text-align: center;">34 John Flynn [16]; see generally also S Gageler, "What is a question of!aw?" (2014) 43 AT Rev 68 (Gage/el'), 68-70, discussing the principles in Collector of Customs v Pozzolanic Ente1prises PO, Ltd (1993) 43 FCR 280; Agfa Gevaert; and Vetter v Lake Macquarie City Council (2001) 202 CLR439 (Vetter).</p><p style="text-align: center;">"AB, [68], citing Kos/as v HIA lns11rance Se11,ices Pi)' Ltd (2010) 241 CLR 390.</p><p style="text-align: center;">36 John Flynn, [16].</p><p style="text-align: center;">37 Vetter, [25]-[26]; Gageler, 69.</p><p style="text-align: center;">38 Rudder v ACT Planning and LandAuthoriO, [2010] ACAT 24; Hamers-Googan and Conimissionerfor Social Housing [2011] ACAT 31.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">45. The approach in Coal and Allied Operations has been followed in other decisions.39</p><p style="text-align: center;">46. Three different types of appeal were considered:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(1) appeal in the strict sense;</p><p style="text-align: center;">(2) appeal by way of rehearing; and</p><p style="text-align: center;">(3) appeal by way of a hearing de nova.</p><p style="text-align: center;">47. The nature of the appeal in a given case was said to depend on the terms of the statute conferring the appeal right, the extent of discretion available within the decision making power and the capacity (or determination) of the appeal body to receive new evidence.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">48. For present pmposes an appeal in a strict sense ("1"), and an appeal by way ofrehearing, ("2"), would involve handling an appeal as a "review" under s 82 of the ACAT Act. A hearing de nova ("3") would involve handling an appeal as a "fresh application".</p><p style="text-align: center;">49. The respondent submits that section s 79 and 82, properly construed, have the effect that an appeal will ordinarily be conducted as a review of pait or all of the decision, save in the case where the interests of justice or effective and timely handling of the application suggest that it should be conducted as an appeal by way of rehearing.</p><p style="text-align: center;">50. Where a question of fact or law has been identified sufficiently within the application, a choice between these alternatives might be made where, for exainple, the matter raised is a mixed question of fact and law which is more conveniently addressed by rehearing.</p><p style="text-align: center;">51. It is only in exceptional cases that an appeal would be heard as an appeal de novo. Without conceding the issue, a choice might be made to hear an appeal de novo where there is an extraordinary matrix oflegal and factual issues and/or allegations offtaud.40</p><p style="text-align: center;">52. Whether it is dealt with as an appeal in the strict sense, or an appeal by way of rehearing (or indeed as a "review" in the strict sense in which that expression is ordinarily used), the role of the Appeal Tribunal is to dete1mine whether the decision of the Original Tribunal is wrong because it "fell into an error of law, made a finding of fact that is clearly wrnng or exercised a discretion on a wrong principle or in a way that is clearly wrong".41 Prnper scmtiny is apprnpriate: the Appeal T1ibmtal must "conduct a real review of the trial and the reasons of the [tr'ibmtal] of first instance". However, the Appeal Tribunal must "give proper allowance to the advantage of the comt of first instance (or an 01iginal trÂ·ibmtal) who saw and heard the witnesses, so that, ordinarily, facts fomtd based on the assessment ofwihtesses will not lightly be oveiturned."42</p><p style="text-align: center;">53. Where the original decision involves the exercise of a discretion, theprinciples in House v King (1936) 55 CLR 499 are applicable. It is not enough for an appellate tr'ibunal to conclude that it would have taken a different course from the original tribunal. What</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">39 Turnbull v New South Wales Medical Board [1976] 2 NSWLR281 which was approved by the High Court in Lacey v Attorney-General of Queensland (201I) 242 CLR 573 and see in particular Theodore/as v Nexus Projects Pty Ltd [2009] ACTSC 149; O'Donnell v Environment Protection Authority [2012] ACTSC 140.</p><p style="text-align: center;">40 Zhang & Yuanv Koh [2011] ACAT 6.</p><p style="text-align: center;">41 Excel, [53].</p><p style="text-align: center;">42 Excel, [53]; Giusida ACTSC, [37].</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">must be evident is that some error has been made in exercising the discretion, such as when the tribunal acts on a wrong principle or mistaken fact, takes hrnlevant matters into consideration, or otherwise makes a decision that is w1reasonable or plainly unjust.43 A decision is discretionary where it involves the application of a general standard to the facts found, in which there is room for value judgments and reasonable differences of opinion44</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">54. .Â  Ordinarily, there are linlited grounds on which one may appeal in relation to evidence. While one may appeal onthe basis that there was no evidence, or no probative evidence, on a paiticular matter before the decision maker, one may not appeal merely on the basis that the decision was "against the evidence" or "against the weight of evidence".45</p><p style="text-align: center;">55. One may not appeal merely on the basis of a disagreement about the findings of fact. To succeed in an appeal on a question of fact, the appellant must demonstrate that the original tribunal relied on on evidence that did not have "a character of reliability and reasonable substance" and it would be sufficient to show that the evidence that was "tenuous or inherently weak or vague".46 Alternatively, if the appellant caimot identify a defect in the evidence before the original tribunal, the appellant must demonstrate that the conclusions drawn from the evidence were "glfil'ingly inlprobable" or "contraiÂ·y to compelling inferences".47</p><p style="text-align: center;">These grounds</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">56. The Appellant aiÂ·gues that there was insufficient evidence to engages 58(2)(b)(ii) and s 58(2)(c) of the Mental Health Act- or put another way, that the facts as found by the Original Tribunal do not fall within the tenns of those provisions. The Respondent submits that the words ins 58(2)(b)(ii) ands 58(2)(c) of the Mental Health Act bear their ordinaiÂ·y meanmg and it was reasonably open for the Original Tribunal to find - as it did - that the Appellant's case falls within these provisions. Grounds I and 2 of the appeal therefore principally involve questions of fact.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Appellant's refusal of treatment-s 58(2)(b)(i) (Ground 1)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">57. The Original Tribunal fotmd that the Appellant refused treatment pursuant to s 58(2)(b)(i) of the Mental Health Act.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">58. The Original Tribunal made this finding having considered the clear and repeated statements of the Appellant that he would comply with treatment,48 as well as the evidence that he was at that time engagh1g voluntarily with mental health services following his discharge from TCH.49 However, the O1iginal Tribunal considered his</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">43 AB, [42], citing House v The King (1936) 55 CLR 499, 504-505, 507. at 652-653</p><p style="text-align: center;">44 Norbis v Norbis (1986) 161 CLR 513, 518-19 (internal footnotes omitted).</p><p style="text-align: center;">45 AushÂ·alian Broadcasting 1)Â·ibunal v Bond & Ors (1990) 170 CLR 321 at 355-356; Collins v Minister/or Immigration and Ethnic Affairs (1981) 58 FLR407 at 410; ComcareAustra/ia v Lees (1997) 151 ALR 647; Hill</p><p style="text-align: center;">v Repatriation Commission (2005) 218 ALR251 at [92].</p><p style="text-align: center;">"GiusidaACTSC,[40]-[41].</p><p style="text-align: center;">47 Chambers v Jobling (1986) 7 NSWLR 1 at 10; Robinson Helicopter Company Incorporated v McDermott</p><p style="text-align: center;">(2016) 90 ALJR 679 at [43]; Mansourv Dangar [2017] ACAT 49 at [25]; CtekHop PtyLtd & Anor vNagle &</p><p style="text-align: center;">Anor [2017] ACAT 92 at [74].</p><p style="text-align: center;">48 Transcript 2 August 2018, p. 9-11, 22.</p><p style="text-align: center;">49 Transcript 2 August 2018, p. 11, 13.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">cunent compliance to be of sho1t duration in light of his history (since at least 2011) of ceasing treatment after advising health authorities that he would continue.so</p><p style="text-align: center;">59. The Respondent submits that this finding was reasonably open to the Original Tribunal, as a matter of both fact and law, and it should not be disturbed.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">60. The Respondent submits that the assessment of whether a person is refusing treatment under s 58(2)(b)(i) cannot be solely subjective, based on the person's stated intentions at or prior to the hearing for the mental health order. It must be objective and take into account evidence that points towards the person being compliant or non-compliant as a matter of fact.</p><p style="text-align: center;">61. In the recent matter of BC (Mental Health) [2018] ACAT 67 the Tribunal adopted this approach and made a PTO notwithstanding evidence that the person in question was compliant with his treatment regime and expressed willingness to take medication.51 The person did not appear to have a history of non-compliance and he had a network of family and other suppmt.52 The Tribunal determined that he refused treatment on the basis that he did not agree with his psychiatrist's mental illness and he indicated that he would not reliably take medication if he disagreed with the diagnosis.53</p><p style="text-align: center;">62. In the present case, the Respondent submits that there are even stronger grounds for the Original Tribunal to take the view that the Appellant refused treatment. The evidence before the Original Tribunal showed that:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ the Appellant had no insight into his mental illness, to the point that he did not accept that he had a mental illness;54</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ the Appellant had recently and repeatedly refused medication, for example, on 6 June 201855 and 4 July 2018,56 and when indicating his willingness to talce medication he stated he would take oral medication but he hated needles;57</p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ the Appellant's recent compliance with treatment appeared to be on the basis that it was the "lesser of two evils", as he wished to avoid going back to hospital, rather than as a result of genuine insight into his illness;58</p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ the Appellant had a history of being discharged from hospital psychiatric wards on the expectation that he would continue trÂ·eatment voluntarily, but each time he quickly lost contact with services. Since 2011, this had occuned three times in Canberra, once in Ballarat, once in Caims and once in Grafton or Lismore.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">50 Statement of Reasons, 2 August2018; Transcript 2 August 2018, p. 29.</p><p style="text-align: center;">51 In the matter of BC (Mental Health) [2018] ACAT 67 ("BC").</p><p style="text-align: center;">52 BC, [24].</p><p style="text-align: center;">53 BC, [18]-[25].</p><p style="text-align: center;">54 PTO Application, p. 3. See also evidence of Appellant, Transcript 12 July 2018, pp 27-28 and 34-35 at which he minimises his presentation at hospital and CenhÂ·elinlcon 4 July 2018, and pp. 40-41 where the Appellent's legal representative indicates her inshuctions are that he does not have a mental illness.</p><p style="text-align: center;">55 PTO Application, p. 4 ("I am not crazy... " "there is no way I will go on any antipsychotic")</p><p style="text-align: center;">56 Transcript 12 July 2018, p. 11, 14 ("he was ve1y much refusing to take any medication").</p><p style="text-align: center;">57 Transcript 12 July 2018, p. 29</p><p style="text-align: center;">58 Transcript 2 August 2018, pp. 4, 6, 10.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">This pattem meant that he had never taken anti-psychotics long-te1m, outside restrictive environments;59 and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">â€¢ the Appellant was at a higher than normal risk of non-compliance, as he had no fixed address and so it would be difficult to follow up with him if he missed appointments. 60</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">63. This evidence was reliable and had reasonable substance; it was not tenuous or inherently wealc or vague. This evidence was properly tested. The Appellant was legally represented and he gave evidence. In particular, the Appellant was provided with the oppmtunity to comment on the Original Tribunal's concerns about his compliance. He gave evidence that the reasons he did not continue with treatment in the past included that he was not able to afford the medication when he was in the US61 and that when he</p><p style="text-align: center;">moved interstate it was difficult to connect with mental health services as he had to prioritise basic needs like finding food.62</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">64. The Original Tribunal heard argument both for and against the malcing of a PTO. His legal representative and the Public Advocate made submissions to the effect that a PTO should not be made. The Original Tribunal described its decision as "a very difficult decision" and it was made by majority.63 Thus, the Original Tribunal reached its conclusions based on a thorough and careful review of the totality of evidence. The Original Tribunal was entitled to weigh this evidence and decide that on balance the Appellant would not accept treatment if a PTO were not in place64 and therefore that he refused treatment within the meaning of s 58(2)(b)(i) of the Mental Health Act.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">65. The Appeal Tribunal should give proper allowance to the Original Tribunal's evidentiary advantage and not ove1tum this decision lightly, merely because another decision may also have been reasonable on the facts. The Respondent submits that the Appellant has not demonstrated any en;or in the original Tribunal's reasoning or findings.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Appellant's risk of deterioration or harm to himself or others<span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>s 58(2)(c) (Ground 2)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">66. The Original Tribunal was unanimous in finding that both criteria ins 58(2)(c)(i) and</p><p style="text-align: center;">(ii) of the Mental Health Act were met.65 These criteria are alternatives. Accordingly, the Appellant would need to demonstrate that the Tribunal was in error on both findings for his appeal to succeed.66</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">67. The Respondent submits that s 58(2)(c)(i) and (ii) of the Mental Health Act involve the exercise of a discretion, as these provisions involve the application of general standards (serious harm or serious deterioration) and value judgments in respect of which</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">59 PTO Application, p. 8.</p><p style="text-align: center;">60 Transcript 2 August 2018, pp, 17-18.</p><p style="text-align: center;">61 Transcript 2 August 2018, pp. 9, 27</p><p style="text-align: center;">62 Transcript 2 August 2018, p. 20.</p><p style="text-align: center;">63 Transcript 2 August 2018, p. 28.</p><p style="text-align: center;">64 Transcript 2 August 2018, p. 30,</p><p style="text-align: center;">65 Transcript 2 August 2018, p. 28 "I can say the Tribuual is in agreement in these respects... We do think that without hÂ·eatment he is likely to do harm to himself... and that also, without hÂ·eatment, his mental state and functioning will seriously deteriorate".</p><p style="text-align: center;">66 QA v Chief Psychiatrist of the ACT [2017] ACTSC 306 ("QA"), [21d]</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">reasonable minds may differ. Accordingly, the principles in House v The King apply and restraint is required in disturbing the decision on appeal.67</p><p style="text-align: center;">Serious harm to himself(s 58{2){c)(i))</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">68. The Original Tribunal found that the Appellant was likely to do serious harm to himself under s 58(2)(c)(i) of the Mental Health Act, as a result of misadventure or self-neglect when unwell. The te1m "ha1m" in s58(2)(c)(i) is not to be given a narrow meaning. It may include, for example, reputational harm as well as physical or financial haim.68</p><p style="text-align: center;">69. The Original Tribunal was persuaded that the Appellant was at risk of harm because his strong and delusional belief system might bring him into conflict with others.69 There was evidence of this occurring in the past, including the incident on 4 July 2018 at the Centrelinlc office and the Appellant's risky behaviours in the caravan pai-Ic near Cairns</p><p style="text-align: center;">in April 2016, as well as evidence that the Appellant had contacts with the AFP while in Canbe1rn in 2012-2013,70 which indicates that his behaviour was bringing him to the</p><p style="text-align: center;">attention of others. More generally, the Appellant's belief system includes features that</p><p style="text-align: center;">may generate conflict, including that he is on a mission to confront and expose the Freemasons.71</p><p style="text-align: center;">70. The Original Tribunal also heard evidence indicati:rig a propensity of the Appellant to self-neglect when he was unwell, including that upon his arrival in BallaiÂ·at in 2011 he had not eaten for 6 days.72</p><p style="text-align: center;">71. The Respondent submits that it was reasonably open to the Original Tribunal to find that the Appellant was at risk of harm pursuantto s 58(2)(c)(i) of the Mental Health Act on the basis of the above evidence. The Appellant has not demonstrated any e1ror in the Original Tribunal's reasoning or findings.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Serious deterioration of his mental state (s 58(2)(c)(ii)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">72. The Original Tribunal accepted the evidence from mental health professionals that the Appellant was likely to suffer serious mental deterioration if he were not treated.73 The</p><p style="text-align: center;">Respondent submits that there was little or no evidence to warrant a contrary finding. The Original Tribunal's reliance on this evidence is therefore without error.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">67 LB v Mental Health ACT [2006] ACTSC 15, [2] (in respect of the equivalent provision in the now-repealed</p><p style="text-align: center;">Mental Health (Treatment and Care) Act 1994).</p><p style="text-align: center;">"QA,[21d].</p><p style="text-align: center;">69 Transcript 2 August 2018, pp. 6, 28 ("he is likely to do harm to himself...potentially how people react to him that leads him to risk"); see also evidence of Ms O'Neil, Transcript 12 July 2018, p. 16.</p><p style="text-align: center;">70 Transcript 2 August 2018, p. 21.</p><p style="text-align: center;">71 PTO Application, pp. 5-7, 10, including assessment (p. 6) that "Wendell's biggest current risk is potentially aggravating others with his driven beliefs and conflict arising".</p><p style="text-align: center;">72 Ballarat Intake Assessment, p. 3.</p><p style="text-align: center;">73 PTO Application, pp. 9-10, including assessment (p. 10) that "the longer he is left with an untreated psychotic illness the worse his prognosis and quality ofrecovery, that could have devastating impacts on his ability to work, have relationships, live and function in society".</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Conclusion on Ground 2</p><p style="text-align: center;">73. The Appellant has not demonstrated any enor in the Original Tribunal's reasoning or findings. In particular, the Appellant has not shown (as would be required to disturb a discretionary decision) that the Original Tribunal:</p><p style="text-align: center;">(a) acted on a wrong principle;</p><p style="text-align: center;">(b) allowed extraneous or irrelevant matters to guide the decision;</p><p style="text-align: center;">(c) mistook the facts;</p><p style="text-align: center;">(d) did not take into account some material consideration; or</p><p style="text-align: center;">(e) if it is not apparent how it reached its decision, the decision on the facts was unreasonable or plainly unjust, and the Original Tribunal failed to properly exercise the discretion.74</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">74. The Original Tribunal reached a careful and considered decision that the Appellant was at risk of sedous haim to himself or serious deterioration. This decision was plainly open on the evidence.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Conclusion</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">75. The Respondent submits the appeal discloses no error of fact or law in the decision of the Original Tribunal and it should be dismissed.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p styl